animal.description:
Up for adoption in Texas: Duke.

Duke is a six-year-old, 72 lb. black lab mix. 

Duke was rescued from a shelter where he was surrendered by his owner who was in the predicted path of Hurricane Laura. 

As it turns out, Duke was one of about 70 total pets in a hoarding situation. He came to Lucky Lab 15-20 lbs. underweight. 

We are pleased to report that Duke has made it through his heartworm treatment and is also now a healthy weight.

Duke is a medium-energy dog who loves to go on brisk walks and smell ALL the smells! He is very strong on a leash and is known to take his walkers for their walks. 

He will require leash training if leash walking is a desired skill. He loves to greet fellow canine walkers with enthusiastic barking. He is not aggressive but is expressing his desire to go say hello.

Duke is also a big fan of sunning in the backyard and rolling in the grass.

Duke loves to be near his humans. He is perfectly content to lay on the kitchen floor while you are making dinner or watch TV with you in the evenings. He is very flexible about hanging out with you. 

In his current foster home, he knows to stay off the furniture. However, he has shown interest in getting on the couch and would be happy to snuggle up once invited. 

He is fully crate trained, and sometimes enjoys going in his crate just for a nap on his orthopedic bed. Duke is crated when no one is home and overnight. He is very curious and LOVES stuffed animals and socks, especially if they belong to his current human siblings.

Duke will do best in a home with other Labs or larger dogs. He has done well in another foster home with Labs and does well meeting new friends his size. Duke is currently in a home with two kids - 11 and 8 years old. While he does well with them, he can get over-excited and want to continue to play even when they are done. He may do best in a home with older children.

Duke is neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, and housebroken. He is ready for his furever home. Could that be yours? If so, please apply on our website now: www.luckylabrescue.com

ZOYA NEEDS YOUR HELP.!!! Foster is selling his home and retiring. Zoya needs an experienced handler and a home of her own.

Zoya MUST be in an environment with no other pets or children.. She would do very well as a guard dog for a business.

While she has been fostered with another dog, she will let the other know when they have pushed her. Best with no other pets in the home.

She has been through a lot not so nice things. 

She would benefit a lot from professional training at this point. Will not place in a home with other pets or children, as there is a lot of territorial aggression for possession and guarding with her with food, toys, space and beds.

She does have a bite history. Regardless of cause of incident, bite is never ok. Therefore, she will only be adopted to a breed experienced strong alpha master handler.

She needs a STRONG ALPHA DOMINATE handler as she will try to over power and step boundaries due to her territorial aggression issues..

Zoya needs a handler that will continue with her exercise program. She is very fit. Currently running 3 miles every day with her current handler.

animal.description:
Meet Miss Lacey! This pretty little lady is a 6- year-old spayed female in need of a new home. She was adopted by her current home about 2 months ago and hit it off with everyone except the male head of household. From what we’ve been told she’s wary of him and has growled a few times in a manner that makes him uncomfortable. 

Like many Rottweilers, Lacey can be aloof with people she doesn't know, but a snuggle bug once she gets to know you. The owner notes she can be growly and fearful sometimes in new circumstances, but once she becomes more comfortable she’s no longer fearful and is friendly. Like a lot of rescues, she gets her confidence from her handler.

Lacey gets along well with the other dogs in the household (male English Setter and a 7-pound Chihuahua mix, mostly just ignoring the latter), and also ignores the geriatric cat that lives in the bedroom down the hall. She’s been around the owner’s goats without issue, and actually helps at feeding time, keeping an eye on her human while the goats are being fed and cared for. 

She rides in the car well and is friendly to those she meets, and is nonreactive to the UPS and mail delivery people. She was sweet and well-behaved for her vet visit, rolling onto her back during the exam. She’s a little chubby right now (no shame!) at 122 pounds, and her owner is working on getting her trimmed down with more activity and feeding regular meals (vs. free feeding). She has good leash manners and walks well on harness or collar, but the no-pull harness is helpful with her large size. 

Her owner tells us Lacey is a love bug – “when she's happy her whole body wiggles (not just her tail), I really enjoy interacting with her, she loves to have all of your attention and returns that. She is very appreciative of a kind home and quiet person and makes sure you know how much she appreciates you. I enjoy helping her learn to be more confident of her actions in our household, she's very attentive, smart, thinks things through, she's a very willing and quick learner, retains and follows rules/boundaries very well. She's beautiful (and will be more so as she becomes fitter), has gorgeous movement, and is really eye-catching.”

We feel Lacey would do best in a quiet home with another dog for a pal, and no children under age 12. Regular exercise will keep her on her weight loss regimen, and she’ll be your best friend forever. 

Please apply to adopt here: https://spdrdogs.org/rescue-referral/how-to-adopt/ 

Washington State or Oregon only – no interstate transports

Visit our Facebook page here: https://www.facebook.com/SPDRRottweilerRescue

animal.description:
Hey there! I'm Magic and I'm a 3 year old, 58lbs, Pitbull Terrier mix.

- I was rescued from the shelter the day I was scheduled to be euthanized as I had injuries in both of my left legs; it's believed that I had endured a traumatic injury that wasn’t treated, which caused my untreated front left paw to curl up due to muscle atrophy. Luckily, it didn't cause me any pain, and instead I used it as a tool to prop myself up.

- I am literally great with everyone! All dogs, men and women, kids, OH! but I do wanna chase cats, so no cats for me please!

- I am a goofy, playful, SUPER sweet boy! I love to give kisses, jump all over you when I see you (something that my foster is working with me on), and LOVE to cuddle!!! 

- I'm really great on the leash, although I can also pull when I get excited and want to say hi to other people and doggos, so I'm learning to be less excited about all that! 

- I already know how to sit and stay, and am fully house trained, because I'm such a smart boy!! 

- Because of the hip surgery I just had, I will need daily physical therapy done by my adopter, about 20-30 mins a day of stretching/rotating my joints, massaging the muscles in both my left legs, so that I can hopefully regain full function of it soon! But that won't last forever, just until I've recovered from my recent surgery!

- I will need a home with very limited stairs, and limited daily exercise like short walks (at first), since I am still recovering from my surgery. That being said, I am a very energetic young boy, and I can't wait to be fully back in action so I can do longer walks/runs and hikes when I've recovered!! 

- My ideal home would be in a home with a yard, and another big doggo to play with, as I have a lot of energy and am a playful goofy pup! 

If you see me online I am still available for adoption! If you are interested in adopting me please fill out an application here: www.hitlivingfoundation.org/adoption-application, and email a video walkthrough of your home and yard to BOTH Nicole@hitlivingfoundation.org AND Marta@hitlivingfoundation.org. Your application will not be counted as valid without your video. You will hear back from us within a few days.

animal.description:
When we first got the call on a dog that was hit by car we were told it was urgent. He was located 45 minutes from Sioux City. When I got there he was crying in pain and literally bleeding to death. The drive home seemed like it took forever. When I got back to Sioux City the Siouxland Animal Hospital was ready when we arrived. We honestly didn’t know if he was going to make it. His pelvis was crushed, his tail was broken in multiple places with the worst break at the base, that’s also where he was losing the most blood from.
After a week in the hospital Dr Saulsbury knew his tail was not savable. The dead tissue was sloughing off. They ended up amputating his tail at the base. After a week an a half of not being able to stand up even on his two front legs he finally started gaining strength. Day 10 he decided that was enough and stood up and took a few steps. After weeks in the hospital he was finally transferred into foster care. There he has remained for rehab.
Savay is an 8 month old shepherd mix. He is a super sweet playful pup. He’s not quite housebroken yet, but he’s working very hard on it. He’s dog friendly and seems to like everyone he meets. He has made great progress since his run in with the car. He’s getting stronger and walking better every day, but still needs to take it slow for a while longer. He may always have a hitch in his getty up but his charming personality makes up for it.
At this point we feel it is time for him to find his forever home. He has been provided with all of the medical attention he needs including neuter and vaccinations. If you feel you could give this guy the best life ever please click on the link below to complete an adoption application. His adoption fee is $135.

https://form.jotform.com/50308432400137

Rudy has arrived! This darling 10 year old, 34 pound terrier mix is quite dashing! Rudy loves people! He rides quietly in the car and has very nice leash manners when walking around his foster's suburban neighborhood. He is completely house trained! His prior owner could no longer afford to care for Rudy, so surrendered him to a local Maryland shelter. Rudy is leash reactive so his ideal forever home is in the suburbs (no city living) with a yard and minimal stairs.

Rudy has luxating patellas but he is still able to go for short walks, maneuver his foster home and handle a few stairs daily. Due to the luxating patellas, a forever home with limited stairs is ideal. To help Rudy feel is best, he will have his patella surgically repaired on March 3. He is still available for adoption and OBG will cover all medical expenses. Rudy has a mild heart murmur that just needs to be monitored without medication and a completely excised lump was a low grade sarcoma. Good news with the complete removal, no additional treatment is needed! Rudy is a happy guy looking for a home in 2021!

To learn more, please send an email to his foster at the link below. 2/2/21 4:21 PM

animal.description:
Bella ACCT-A-80046

Intake: Owner Surrender
Sex: Female
Age: 2Y
Altered: Yes

Meet Bella! This brindle beauty is about 2 years old and full of love. She's the tug-o-war queen and happily entertains herself with her rope and Kong toys. She indulges in long naps in her kennel or bed throughout the day, while coming over every once in a while for a nice rub.

She enjoys walks around the neighborhood and is great on the leash. Bella's a little timid of loud noises and busy intersections but is getting more comfortable on each walk. She will need to be the only pet in the home, as she is reactive to other dogs. Bella will need time to warm up, but will be extremely loyal to her new family.

Bella is crate trained and working on house training. She loves working for treats and has already learned "sit.

**VIDEOS**
Bella Outside: https://youtu.be/TFxoTa8bpGs
Bella Walking https://youtu.be/Y_px1LdzqHQ
Bella knows sit https://youtu.be/amB6XMf27l0
Bella in Run https://youtu.be/G8o2bqLZROk

Medical Observation:
1/24 (Vet Check)-- Initially calm and quiet in kennel when approached, but became quickly overstimulated and jumping barking at cage door. Will start trazodone at low dose with room to increase if necessary.
1/5 (Vet Check) -- Patient has had a reported limp since 12/3 that appears responsive to medical management but has not resolved. Patient seems uncomfortable in the left tarsus and hip joints and has some muscle atrophy in the left leg. Recommend further work up at full service hospital with radiographs and sedated orthopedic examination.
1/1 (Per Clinic) -- Unable to examine due to behavior. Came in for right hind leg limping, seen limping out side, recommend x-rays.
12/3 (Vet Check) -- The patient is a young adult large breed dog with a reported history of dragging one of her back legs. On orthopedic exam today, she appeared to be comfortable on all four limbs and no dragging was observed.
11/29 (Physical Exam) -- Red eyes, hair loss, BAR

Behavior Observation:
1/24 (Per Staff)-- Kennel Presentation: Easy to leash/social. On approach, barking with front paws on kennel door. Sat for treat and held sit while being leashed. No issues returning to kennel or removing leash. Started barking once kennel door was closed.
Leash Skills: Pulls Moderately On Leash
Handleability: Loose/Allows all handling. Allows handling all over with loose body. In yard, frequently returns to handler for pets.
Tag: No interest. Would run up to handler when called but would not follow when tag was initiated.
Toys: Interest but does not take possession. Chased tennis balls when tossed but lost interest when she got there.
Color Level: Blue. Previously eval'd as Blue. This eval would be Gold but other behavior notes indicate reactivity when returning to kennel for some handlers so leaving as Blue.
1/12 (Per Vet)-- unable to handle awake, sedated exam
1/5 (Per Volunteer) -- Volunteer mentioned that she had Bella out and while outside Bella was affectionate, social, and soliciting pets. On return to kennels Bella's demeanor changed and she began to growl and snap (not sure if she snapped at handler or at leash).
1/5 (Per Volunteer)-- Kennel Presentation---Easy to leash/social---Easy to leash and remove from kennel. Began hard barking once back in kennel. Jumping on kennel door and barked at me. Tired to escape.
Leash Skills---Pulls Moderately On Leash---Eager to explore and go for a walk. Pulls on leash but manageable due to her size
Handleability---Loose/Allows all handling---Very sweet and allowed all handling. He did not solicit much attention on walk but once in run stayed close to me.
Tag--No interest---Not interested in playing. Preferred sniffing
Toys---No interest--Chased a ball but did not retrieve or show interest. 
Knows Sit and is housetrained. We passed one dog and Bella showed no interest
1/5 (Per Previous Foster) -- Bella loves cheese and peanut butter, knows "sit and was starting to understand "shake and "stay. She is crate-trained, and not fully housebroken but had been taking outside about every 2-3 hours during the day and rewarding all outdoor bathroom breaks; started to bark when she needed to go out (most of the time). Bella was reactive to other dogs and young children, would probably do best as the only pet. She's a super chewer, but only on her toys!
1/4 (Intake) -- Returned from foster due to continued reactivity towards strangers, dogs, and children that has not improved over duration of foster care.
1/4 (Per Previous Foster) -- She barks at all people and dogs when approached, and tends to pull towards them. She'll bark at some people/dogs that are further away (across the street or down the block), especially if they speak or acknowledge her. We've had some friends throw her cheese from a distance and she does calm down for a bit. Once they stop giving her treats, she'll start barking until we walk away from them. Yesterday an Amazon delivery person opened our front door, she was barking and tried to get to him. In all of the excitement, she somehow jumped up and bit my hand. It didn't break the skin.
12/3 (Per Staff) -- Standing at front of kennel with tail tucked and shaking, but when handler approached wagged tail slightly - remained tense and shaking. When kennel door opened Becca retreated to the back of the kennel and was avoidant of handling. Handler kneeled down in kennel and was able to loop Becca, as soon as loop went over her head she turned around and exited kennel. Pulled hard on leash through kennels, and remained tense on leash at times flashing around, but then would settle down. Once in run stayed close to handlers soliciting attention and leaning in for pets with wagging tail and loose body, but would yawn, whimper and pant simultaneously. Handler had to step back into kennel and Becca followed behind, no issues removing leash. 
12/2 (Per Staff) -- Attempted to remove from kennel but Becca is very nervous. At front of kennel when handler approached and would sniff hand but retreat. Would return to front of kennel for cheese and stayed at front when kennel door was opened and leash presented. Easily leashed but then retreated to back of kennel. Would come back to handler when lured with cheese. Would take cheese gently from hand and allowed handler to slowly pet but would not exit kennel despite coaxing and cheese. Spent a few minutes in kennel with Becca and she would allow petting and solicit attention from handler but could not get her to exit. Leash easily removed.
11/29 (Per Vet Staff) -- Unable to get weight or examine teeth due to behavior, Fractious.

animal.description:
Meet Meg!

15-year-old Meg was brought to the Long Beach Shelter as a stray and arrived at Frosted Faces on January 5th. We took her to College Animal Hospital where we learned she has severe dental disease and cannot see due to cataracts. We are waiting to get to know her to determine whether she can handle dental surgery. In her first few days here, Meg was quiet and often napping, if not being held by volunteers. Understandable for a 15 year old, 6 lb. blind little girl who has been through a lot in the past weeks!

Fortunately, Meg went on an extended 3-week Frosted Fling with who gave Meg a loving, safe place to decompress and recover from dental surgery. Meg settled in nicely and got along well with the six other small dogs there. Here's what else we've learned:

Although Meg is blind, she gets around well and found her way to the water bowl and dog beds on on the first day! She even found her way up the ramp, through the door, and into the house! Meg has a great appetite, and seems to be potty trained. Meg enjoys exploring the yard, being held, going on stroller rides. and taking naps in cozy beds.

Her Fling Mom shares, "Meg is a sweet, old lady, She lays quietly in your arms, totters around on stiff legs, and sleeps soundly. She loves her routine of food, naps, outdoor time, and snuggles.

Meg is ready for her forever family!"

Meg is back onsite at Frosted Faces Foundation. Stop by to meet here during an upcoming Open House!

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm.

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption

fees, and we help with medical costs!

Apply here to become a family:
www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated 1/29/21 KG

Once Cody arrived in the Big Apple he went to his new foster home and settled in very quickly. He get his dinner of kibbles and green beans and his snacks are apples, carrots, berries and other fruits and veggies. 
He’s continuing to lose weight and loves being allowed to run around in the yard. He does get along with other dogs but can be a little humpy with one of the cute girls there and his favorite blanket. Other than that, he is simply pawfect! And he has a few extra toes on his back feet too! Those have to weigh something ?
Cody is currently around 29lbs, is about 7 or 8 from best guesstimate and just a love cuddler. 
Cody is located in Bellmore NY

animal.description:
This beautiful boy goes by the name of Sarge!  Sarge may not have been given the right conditions in those first important weeks of his life where puppies learn how to behave and be social dogs.  He has not yet learned that mouthing and nipping (as puppies do) is not acceptable behavior for a young dog like him.

However, we strongly feel that given the right conditions and training Sarge will make someone a great dog.  Someone with experience in working with German Shepherds will be necessary for Sarge to succeed.  

Sarge wants so badly to be loved, and once he gets to know you, he doesn’t want you to leave him behind.  He will cry and whine – because he just wants to be with people. There will be a need to work on his separation anxiety issues and have some patience.  He will also need a quiet and slow decompression period once he is adopted into a home.  Due to this initial display of separation anxiety, we don't believe Sarge would do well in an apartment/condo/townhome setting.  

Sarge doesn’t like raised voices and any form of training can only be done with positive reinforcement methods, no aversive training as this will definitely not give the desired result with a dog like Sarge.  He is sensitive, but so lovable!  

Sarge enjoys toys and treats so there is plenty of room for motivation during training. When Sarge gets over stimulated, he may exhibit some naughty grabbing/mouthing behaviors. He does respond to a “sit” and a treat though so he can calm down that way.

For you to consider adopting Sarge we would like you to visit him a few times at the rescue so he can get to know you.  We are only accepting applications from local folks with German Shepherd experience.  If you are interesting in making Sarge a part of your family, please visit www.crcpa.org, and complete an application!

Sadie Mae is a VERY sweet, very friendly apprx 10 year old beagle mix. She gets along with dogs and we think she would do great with kids. She is getting spayed 1/9, microchipped, up to date on vaccines and prevention and heartworm negative. Her adoption fee is $150. Sadie Mae does suffer from possible IVDD and may have flare up back issues ongoing throughout the rest of her life but it doesn't stop her from living her best life! From Sadie's foster mom: Hi, I'm Sadie! I am a distinguished lady who would never admit her age, although I'm 12. I may have arthritis but am doing well on my feet. I like friends of all sizes, genders, and play energies if they are not feline. I do not like to share my food with other of the 4-legged variety. However, I don't mind it when mom takes or moves my bowl and I love pets while I eat. A little about me: FOOD FOOD FOOD!! I chase squirrels and small animals with glee; I LOVE bones, soft snuggle beds, pettings, and adventurous walks. I make the best class/office mate because I just want to sit and watch. I have arthritis but have been getting along great (with minor accommodations) and rebuilding my muscles while supporting my joints. What accommodations do you ask? I watch my weight and have a higher fat/calcium diet. I also need a small steroid, every other day, until cleared by the vet. Stairs can be a little tough but I'm ok with a small step up or a ramp.

Sadie will be ready to meet her forever family after her spay on 1/9. Please fill out this link for the application if you'd like to be approved to meet her https://toolkit.rescuegroups.org/of/f?c=SGVJMGQY

animal.description:
***Jack needs a fence***

Jack is a year old possible lab/border collie mix. He is neutered, up to date on shots, wormed, microchipped, and heartworm free. He is house trained and gets along with other dogs and cats. He needs work on leash skills. We know from reported sightings that Jack was on his own for a while and traveled some distance before he was trapped. He can be skittish at times, but when he relaxes, he loves attention. He needs a family that has time, patience, and can make him feel safe. He does like to be with other dogs once he gets to know them. 

Jack is a work in progress. He is very skittish, easily spooked. He shies from the leash but is being worked with on this as well as taking walks in the neighborhood. Jack needs hard chew toys as he loves to chew. He will sit nicely when asked and is not a jumper. He is very loyal and will stick close to his family member and loves to be given pets and lovins. He needs someone with time and patience to work with him. Training would be great. Jack has lots of love to give the right family!

Current pets must be up to date on vaccines, dogs on heartworm prevention with a good history. We are requiring that Jack has an above ground fence as he is a flight risk. 

If your home/family has time for this sweet guy, please fill out an application at: 

https://www.pawsofadamscounty.com/adoption-foster-app

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Jack is good with other dogs and cats and so very loving and loyal.

animal.description: Maya is a gorgeous 7 year old German Shepherd in the prime of her life. She is an active dog that enjoys being with people and would do best as the only dog. This makes her all the more devoted to her owner and will hand out kisses non-stop! Maya was quick to learn her commands of sit, down, and stay. Maya even has a shake command where she will shake paws with you. She does like to play with a ball and will carry it around for a while and even spend some time chewing on it. Making her most happy is when she gets to play fetch. Maya loves going for car rides. She likes people over other animals, so might be best as the only pet in the house. She appears to be housetrained and does pretty well on leash. She does love going on long walks. She also likes to cuddle. If playing fetch, getting kisses, cuddling, and going on long walks in the park appeal to you . . . then you need to fetch this dog for yourself! I'm available for a 30 day adoption trial through the Foster to Adopt program. If you are interested in giving me a test adoption run in your home, please sign up for an adoption consultation. Learn more about our virtual adoption process .

animal.description:
Lily is living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet her.

Lily is not eligible for foster and will be a straight adoption.

Age: ~3.5 years
Weight: ~79lbs
Housebroken: No, Lily will need work on this through a strict schedule and positive reinforcement training. Her pottying accidents typically stem from anxiety of being left alone.
Crate trained: No, Lily doesn't love the crate and has instead been left with free roam to a sectioned off area when her fosters have left her alone. She does have some separation anxiety and will take time to settle. She will need an adopter that doesn't have shared walls and can continue to work on training for this.
Dog sociability: Selective with her dog friends. May be a match for some, but not all. She is protective over resources and would prefer not to live in a home with another dog. While on walks, Lily is leash frustrated and eager to meet other dogs. She will howl and pulls strongly towards other dogs
Cat sociability: Not a match
Kids: Not a match
Ideal home: Lily is looking for a calm, adult-only home that is home often (during normal times, not just COVID) as she has separation anxiety. She prefers a quiet neighborhood and is not a match for a high-rise/elevator building. 

Calling all malamute lovers. Lily is one majestic pup looking for her forever home! She's smart, stoic, and sometimes sassy... your typical malamute. She's very calm and relaxed inside, and just loves being in the comfort of the same room as her humans. If she cuddles up next to you, consider yourself the lucky one! This girl needs patience, but she'll warm up in no time... the fastest way to her heart is through belly rubs and hot dogs. She loves learning new tricks to keep her mind sharp. She knows sit, shake, down, and is working on play dead (bang). Her fosters have a lot of fun working on a new trick each week, she's very smart and will do anything for a treat! She's working on potty training. Like clockwork, she starts her day at 7:30am. Her signals are very subtle, and she's very polite. If this girl sits for you, it's go-time. She loves long walks and is great on a leash. This girl would LOVE a backyard to zoom around off leash in. She'll chase after a tennis ball but don't expect her to bring it back. She'd rather run circles in the snow, and sniff out hidden treats. She hasn't quite learned the second half of fetch yet. Overall this girl is a very loving and loyal companion. There's nothing like the love of a malamute.

Lily's adoption fee is 300. She is spayed, up to date on core vaccines, microchipped and heartworm negative.

***We are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application. ***

animal.description:
Meet Ella!
*BREED EXPERIENCE REQUIRED*

Breed: Siberian Husky
Estimated DOB: 12/14/2009
Sex: Female - Unaltered due to age
Weight: 47-50 lbs (Underweight) 
Rescued From: SC

At 11-years-old, Ella is more than deserving to live out her golden years curled up on a sofa with her person softly scratching her behind the ears, especially after the heartbreak she’s endured in her years.  Ella and her sister, Bellevue once had a family to call their own. A change in circumstance, however, left them in the care of a family member, who while they gave Ella and Belivue a space outside on their property, they were then virtually forgotten and neglected. The tips of their ears are missing due to fly bites, and their skinny frames indicated their meals were infrequent. To add insult to injury, Ella also tested positive for Heartworms. This, however, is where you come in.

Ella is looking for a loving home that can show her she is worthy of love and care, a home where she can be confident she will be fed each day and have a warm and cozy place to lay her head. In fact, she is loving her recent discovery of the sofa, although she may need a little help getting up. She is sweet and affectionate, and she is learning the nuances of living in a home more and more every day. Ella is looking for a family who can show her the true meaning of golden years and make sure the rest of her days are filled with comfort and love.

Things to know about Ella:
- Surrendered to the shelter with Belivue when the owner could no longer care for them
- Sweet senior looking for a home to live out her golden years
- Ella is a hospice dog who is Heartworm Positive and unable to go through treatment due to age 
- Loves people of all ages
- Sweet and affectionate
- Low / Medium energy
- Will play with foster dad here and there, but mostly calm
- Loves walks on the long lead
- Enjoys sniffing outside
- Likes car rides
- Enjoys the couch 
- Loves treats
- Dog Friendly - Coexists with other dogs - Prefers people over other dogs
- No cats please
- Working on house training 
- Crate Trained -  will whine, but calms down
- Would make a good companion dog in a calm household

Learn how to make Ella a member of your family at TLCrescuePA.com/adopt

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Cassie!  I am 4 years old, and arrived at the shelter when my owner could no longer care for me.  I am a big girl, weighing approximately 80 lbs.

In my previous home I was mainly outside in a fenced yard.  I am seeking a dog-savvy home who people who are willing to be patient with me as I come out of my shell and build trust.  I am very loving and gentle with the people here at the shelter, and just want to soak up attention and pets!

Though I was raised mostly outside, I have good leash manners, and am potty-trained.  I am a calm, gentle giant, and I don’t seem to mind cats when I pass by them on walks.  I wasn’t socialized with other dogs very much, so I would do best in a dog-less home (though I don't seem to mind mellow male dogs much).  I'm very dog-selective and, as an Anatolian, I tend to guard my area from other dogs - sounding off if an unfamiliar dog walks by my kennel.  If you are unfamiliar with livestock guarding dog breeds like mine, please do your research (though I have NOT lived with livestock and am not trained to guard livestock).   I do not have experience with children, and would do best in a home with no children under 10.  I am not a "go everywhere with you" dog, and would prefer to be homebody and be comfortable on my own turf.

My back knees are stiff, due to what the vet suspects is CCL disease.  This is common in breeds like mine.  Here is a link for more information on CCL disease: 
https://caninearthritis.org/article/ccl-ruptures-tears/ . I am on anti-inflammatories now (rimadyl/carprofen) and will likely need to stay on these medications, or at the very least be on high-quality joint supplements.  I arrived with some cysts on my back that are not harmful and not bothering me.  The vet said to just leave them alone unless they're bugging me.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Cassie!  I am 4 years old, and arrived at the shelter when my owner could no longer care for me.  I am a big girl, weighing approximately 80 lbs.

In my previous home I was mainly outside in a fenced yard.  I am seeking a dog-savvy home who people who are willing to be patient with me as I come out of my shell and build trust.  I am very loving and gentle with the people here at the shelter, and just want to soak up attention and pets!

Though I was raised mostly outside, I have good leash manners, and am potty-trained.  I am a calm, gentle giant, and I don’t seem to mind cats when I pass by them on walks.  I wasn’t socialized with other dogs very much, so I would do best in a dog-less home (though I don't seem to mind mellow male dogs much).  I'm very dog-selective and, as an Anatolian, I tend to guard my area from other dogs - sounding off if an unfamiliar dog walks by my kennel.  If you are unfamiliar with livestock guarding dog breeds like mine, please do your research (though I have NOT lived with livestock and am not trained to guard livestock).   I do not have experience with children, and would do best in a home with no children under 10.  I am not a "go everywhere with you" dog, and would prefer to be homebody and be comfortable on my own turf.

My back knees are stiff, due to what the vet suspects is CCL disease.  This is common in breeds like mine.  Here is a link for more information on CCL disease: 
https://caninearthritis.org/article/ccl-ruptures-tears/ . I am on anti-inflammatories now (rimadyl/carprofen) and will likely need to stay on these medications, or at the very least be on high-quality joint supplements.  I arrived with some cysts on my back that are not harmful and not bothering me.  The vet said to just leave them alone unless they're bugging me.  

My adoption fee is $150 (+ $20 county dog license, if residing within Jefferson County).  I have been spayed, am up to date on my rabies and DAPP vaccines, and have been micro-chipped too!  IF YOU ARE SEEING MY BIO, I AM STILL UP FOR ADOPTION - PLEASE FOLLOW THE DIRECTIONS BELOW.

animal.description:
Hello, my name is Sparky and I am a 7 year young Lab/Shephard mix. 
I miss my mom and dad.  You see, everything was fine until one day they decided to divorce and then I went to live in different places. I was just left behind and I don't know why. I thought they loved me.  I am happy here at my foster home and my foster mom tells me not to worry and that my forever family will soon find me. You see, she wants to make sure that they are perfect for so that I am never get left behind again.

 I love to play with all the other dogs in my foster home. My favorite thing is to chase a tennis ball.  Man, I can do that for hours without getting bored.  I also like all the toys that squeak but my foster mom tells me that I should stop chewing them.  She says they are all in toy heaven.  I just love, love my toys but mostly playing fetch with my human.  I am a bit of an escape artist so my foster mom says that I would do best in a fenced yard. 
I am a gentleman and I know to tell you when I have to go outside to do my business.  I also know my crate but I don't need it.  I know that I have to get some training walking on leash because no one thought me that I can't pull my human. Don't worry, I am a smart guy and I'll figure that out.  Just get me some training ok? 

Another one of my favorite things is to sit on your lap and shower you with kisses!  What did you say? that I can't be a lap dog because I am 68 lbs?  Watch me! I will distract you with kisses and smiles while I sit on your lap. We will both be very comfortable. Let's meet and you will fall in love with me. I now you won't leave me behind. 

Love
Sparky


To meet Sparky please complete an adoption application at www.treasuredanimalrescueinc.org.   Due to the large number of applications we might not be able to get back to you so please check our website for updates on Sparky's adoption status.  www.treasuredanimalrescueinc.org 

We cannot adopt out of the state of IL 

Sparky's home is located in the city of Chicago/Galewood area

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email Dena at DenaE@k-9lifesavers.org
You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.
Dog's Name: Toby
Estimated Breed : Australian Shepherd Mix
Approximate Age: 1 year
Approximate Weight: approx. 37 lbs
Currently Living at: Boarding
Adoption Fee: $300
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Meet Toby! He is a gorgeous boy who is looking for a loving forever home...but not just any home will do! This guy has some special requirements in order to succeed in his forever home. He is a very sweet guy, but does have some food resource guarding that will need special attention. Because this food resource guarding has to do with humans (and probably dogs as well) we can't adopt to a family with children as this guy is likely to snap that food right out of the little ones fingers as they walk by with a snack. Because of the resource guarding, and we don't know exactly to what extent since he is in boarding, we do require a family with prior dog experience; no first timers...sorry!! He is an Aussie, and this breed is well known for being high energy and smart...this gorgeous guy is no exception! Because he is high energy and smart, we are looking for a family with a large fenced back yard for him to be able to expend his energy safely and someone willing to work with him on training and playing games to also keep him mentally stimulated. He may not be housebroken, but it's hard to tell when they are in boarding, but I suspect that would be fixed in short order with focused attention. If you can accommodate this guys needs, please apply! Once we have an approved adopter he will be removed from the website.
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
Rory is an itty bitty guy who was saved just hours before euthanasia. He's leary of people at first but you just have to let him love you at his own pace and once he trusts you that love comes so easy. He prefers not to have anyone near his food bowl when he's eating, but other than that he really doesn't ask for much. Rory would prefer a quiet household with no small children. He's ok on a leash but also likes to stroll around the yard, so a fenced yard would be a bonus for him. He gets along with the other dogs in his foster home, but slow introductions work best for him. We think Rory is at least 5-6 years old. He's up to date on vaccines, microchipped and neutered.

Interested in adopting me? To fill out an application visit 3 Hearts 4 Paws. Please note: we do not adopt out of state unless it is within 1-2 hours of us.

animal.description:
Adorable, energetic pup Rudy is looking for his forever family!

Rudy is a very happy, social 45lb guy who is still working on perfecting his puppy manners. He is crate trained, and just about fool proof when it comes to potty training (although if he is left alone in the crate for too long he may have an accident.) Rudy would really love a family who spends most of their time at home, or who can bring him along on adventures! He is still a bit insecure at times which can cause overstimulation, and absolutely needs an experienced owner who will set boundaries, give him direction and reassure him while building confidence. Rudy must also have an active family willing to take him on daily structured walks - he’s amazing on leash!

He does enjoy the company of other dogs, especially those around his size. He would be best in a home without small dogs or cats, as he wants to wrestle with his furry friends! Another medium sized dog who is extremely social, tolerant, and confident would be the best match. Rudy is extremely attentive and smart – he already knows sit, and wait, and is learning other commands. He would benefit from additional obedience training with a professional. The key to Rudy’s happiness is a lap to snuggle on! We prefer that Rudy goes to a home with kids age 13 or older, or adults only.

If you are interested in adopting Rudy, please go to our website and fill out an adoption application!

animal.description:
If you are patient, have a dog that needs a playmate for the occasional romp, and a comfy chair that needs nested then Ash is the dog for you. He prefers to spend his days laying in the sun outside or curled up in his favorite chair. He makes time to run with the six-month-old puppy at his fosters and doesn’t mind extra energy and will let the pup know when playtime is over.

He has lots of people trust issues & is not a ‘cuddle me’ dog...yet. He doesn’t like to be left alone and would do best with a pup mate to curb separation anxiety. He hasn’t found a love for dog toys or treats yet but cheese is wonderful!

Ash is neutered, up to date on vaccines, microchipped, and is in the beginning stages of heartworm treatment, as he is positive for heartworms. 

If you are interested in adopting Ash, fill out an application at https://www.eunoiarescue.org/adopt.

Seamus is a very energetic hound mix. He loves dogs and people—cats are to be determined. He is great on the leash and is crate trained! He loves to go on walks/runs and playing with our dogs in the backyard. Just keep an eye on him or have a very high fence, because the boy can jump!

Seamus is still getting used to being kept indoors. He seems to be very comfortable outside, but being kept in the house is new for him. We are working with him on not getting on the furniture and getting all the snuggles that we can! He’s not sure what all this love stuff is about, lol!

Seamus is neutered, microchipped, up to date on vaccines and heartworm negative.

If you are interested in adopting Seamus, fill out an application at https://www.eunoiarescue.org/adopt.

animal.description:
Are you looking for an adventurous spunky cheerful cuddle obsessed goofball? Do you have a spacious backyard that we can romp around? Are you ready to be followed around your house and protected by your very own four-legged bodyguard while you pee? Well look no further because the companion of your dreams is ready to meet you! Weighing in at 70 lb and missing half her tail and all her bottom front teeth is Charlie, German Shepherd extraordinaire.

Gets along well with all humans big and small. She does show stalking behavior towards smaller dogs and cats so she would probably fit best in a one dog household or with a male companion of comparable to slightly smaller size. 

At 6.5 years old she's still energetic but can focus on favorite activities such as chewing on Bones and treat-filled Kongs. She is potty trained, knows sit and lay but she does pull a little on walks. It's just because she's excited sniffing out her furrever home!

animal.description:
Boone is an exuberant hound mix from a rural shelter in Manning, SC looking for his forever home. He is an energetic goofball who loves going on long walks, tracking new smells, and meeting new friends (canine or human). He is an incredibly social dog, and loves being around other dogs, so he would do best if he went to a household with siblings. He is a great pup to take on adventures because he’s so friendly, curious, and athletic. He’s high energy and leggy, so would do best in a house with a yard where he can stretch his legs (or with somebody committed to taking him to the dog park).

We do think this is his first time living in a household, so he’d do best with a family willing to put in a little bit of time to train him. He’s a very good boy and has never shown any aggression whatsoever, but he still needs to learn how to conduct himself in a home that isn’t fully puppy-proofed. He can be vocal, but would probably settle down if he had a buddy to play with. Boone is crate trained and sleeps quietly in his crate all night. He is currently learning how to walk on a leash (most of his pulling happens when he spots a potential new friend and can’t wait to get over there and meet them). He has had no accidents in the house, but he hasn’t been left unattended for any length of time to truly test that. We have not tested him with cats or children. 

Boone is neutered, up to date on vaccines, microchips and went through heartworm treatment. 

If you are interested in adopting Boone, fill out an application at https://www.eunoiarescue.org/adopt.

In saying this she needs someone who does not mind giving her attention, she has no desire to be crated all day or night, she wants to be with you. animal.description:
Hey there! I'm Vivica and I'm so beyond ready to find my forever home! I'm beautiful and smart and athletic and I will do just about anything to jump in your lap and lick your whole face once I love you. The thing is, I've been through a lot in my couple of years here on Earth, and because of that I can be pretty anxious and terrified of people I don't know. Men and kids are particularly scary, but even women I don't know can take me a second to warm up to. I've come a long way in my foster home, but I need someone who is patient and willing to continue to work with me. I'm currently on anxiety medication, and I will mostly likely need to continue taking them to feel a little safer and calmer wherever I end up. I get along with all doggies, but I want to chase and pounce on kitties and they don't seem to like that. My foster momma says I'm part kangaroo because I can jump 5 ft straight up in the air from a sit. I would love someone who lives a quiet lifestyle who can devote lots of time to me and teach me how to do fun tricks. I know my person is out there and that it's going to take a while to find them... But I'm willing to wait. If you're interested in meeting me, put in an application with

Pawsitive Tails Dog Rescue

today! I can't wait to meet you!! Love, Vivi

Vivica's adoption fee is $75 and she is up to date on vaccines, dewormed, current on flea and heartworm prevention, heartworm negative, spayed and microchipped.

animal.description: I'll bet you're looking for Amelia!Amelia runs so fast that she becomes airborne, while still in control, like a pilot. Amelia likes to have her food served on a snuffle mat instead of in a plain ol' bowl. She is a fan of stuffies with squeaker and playing fetch with a tennis ball. When it's warm outside she likes playing in a kiddie pool. Amelia loves going on walks and does pretty darned good on leash. Amelia would prefer to be the only dog in her new home, if you don't mind. animal.description: This dreamy dog is Dolly and, lucky for you, she's looking for a forever home. Dolly is about a year old and weighs around 40 pounds. She's snuggly, sweet, affectionate, and leans into you for pets. Dolly is already housetrained, good on leash, and is learning to love her kennel. She's also an excellent napper, in case you were wondering! She loooooooves other dogs and would benefit from having a canine pal in her new home. Dolly is shy and fearful around new people and things, which is understandable, given that she lived in a garage with no contact with the outside world. So, she needs a home with patient people who don't have a lot of visitors. She also needs a fenced yard and can't live in an apartment because all those noises are way too scary for this girl. Call or text The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387 for more info on Dolly! She's spayed, up to date on vaccines, microchipped, and ready to roll. Rescued off of the highway with severe dog bites, Atticus overcame the odds and blossomed into the goofy, sweet, and affectionate pup he was meant to be. He loves chasing balls (doesn't return them yet!), chewing on Kongs filled with treats, and lazing around the house. His athleticism, especially his vertical leap and running, definitely qualifies him to play for the Spurs. He is house trained and good with other dogs and kids. 

Atticus is a four-year-old yellow Lab Pit mix who weighs 50 lbs. 

Send us your application for Atticus today!

https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/adopt/FBF/Dog

animal.description:
Peanut is a jaunty fellow that loves people of all ages. He enjoys a good neck rub and will snort with pleasure. He is 4.5 years old and has some health issues that have prevented him from being neutered. He does like to leave his mark around the house. He takes 4 medications each day. He knows pill time also means a yummy treat and he makes sure you don't forget them. Peanut loves to nap and swears he doesn't snore, but he does. He gets along with other dogs and cats. His doggy dna shows he is 75% Chihuahua, 12.5% Maltese and12.5% terrier group. We think he is 100% lovable.

If you'd like to meet Peanut, just fill out an application at www.pawsitivetailskc.org and his foster will contact you to set that up. Peanut's adoption fee has been waived as he does have a heart issue that will require lifetime medication.

animal.description:
Just when you think you've already had the most perfect dogs, along comes a pooch that is so amiable and a joy to have around - easy and almost carefree. Joey loves to curl up and sleep all day.  The secure sleep of a rescued street dog. Joey is a 4 yr old male blue heeler mix that weighs 39# . His right front leg needed to be removed as it was damaged beyond repair before coming into the rescue group. The wound has totally healed, and Joey has good mobility. He gets around just fine with 3 legs.  Although he shouldn’t go jogging, he can go for long walks, can easily go up/down a flight of stairs, and he can jump up on the sofa and bed (so he can sleep with his foster at night). It is important for you to provide regular exercise to keep his muscles toned and his remaining 3 legs strong, and keep him at his ideal weight. Joey chases squirrels in the yard, and runs and plays with the resident dogs. He is housebroken reliably for at least 7 hours. He loves having a back yard to roam but he's good at squeezing through small spaces. He's escaped a few times out of the fenced back yard, looking for his person working in the front yard. If he can’t find his person, he might wander around the block looking for him, otherwise he will come when you call him. He gets very attached to the person feeding and walking him. He must have some hound dog in him because he howls when he's looking for his attached person because they are out of his sight. Even if someone else is home. Because of this, he would not be good in shared wall housing. He is not destructive. He may have a bit of separation anxiety but he doesn't act out other than cry a little and search the house. This dog would love to go with you on trips and car rides as long as it's not too hot, and is able to jump into the vehicle.  Joey gets along with people and dogs. No cat experience. 
His food drive is very strong, making him easier to train with a little treat.  Since he is food driven, young kids might not be appropriate with Joey since he will grab food given the opportunity. Joey will countersurf, so you can’t leave food within his reach. However, he is gentle and otherwise safe.  The fosters have yet to see any display of aggression. 
He really likes his dog housemates. Joey is smart and learns quickly. His favorite things are sleeping, eating, walking (he hails from a warmer state and doesn’t like the cold, so wears a jacket outside) and chewing on butcher bones. He is very sweet, but not overly affectionate – just needs to be near his person. He must be by your side at all times when you are home. Joey will adopt you, and tends to favor one person in the home – he would be perfect for a single person. 
Joey thrives on routine – he needs to be able to anticipate what happens and when. So establish your routine from the first day he comes into your home. Feed him at the same times. If it will be an expectation to crate him, the put him in the kennel when you leave the house. The fosters did not crate him because he doesn’t have accidents and is not destructive. If you work outside the home, or do volunteer work, he will learn how long you will be gone. Likes to know when it’s time to go for a walk. Joey just likes structure. 
He was previously neutered, and is current on distemper, rabies and bordetella vaccinations. On October 2 he had a dental cleaning, and 3 cracked/broken teeth were extracted. Amputation of the right front leg was done on October 16. His microchip is registered to Second Chance.  Even though his mobility is good now, there may come a time in his old age that he will sometimes need to be lifted into the vehicle, or onto the bed – it would be best if his adopter would physically be able to do this. The adopter should be home much of the time. We will not adopt him into an apartment. His adoption fee is $350 . Call 651-771-5662 if you would like to meet Joey.

animal.description:
Meet Boscoe!!

He arrived to NW Indiana from one of our shelter partners in the Houston, TX area.  His foster mom in Schererville, IN says that he is really sweet and gentle.  He loves to play with other dogs and to walk on a leash.  He doesn't pull, but does like to try to chase birds.  

He loves to cuddle and give kisses, but he also doesn't mind laying down in his crate and taking a nap.  

Here is a video of him with his foster sibling: 
https://youtu.be/0C47-NryvQA

If you are interested in this beautiful, fun dog who would love to cuddle with you, apply today!  

Here is another video of him from right off transport: https://youtu.be/55cvNy3AGhA

He is 1 yr old, neutered, up to date on vaccines, rabies and has a microchip.

Adoption Process:

- please fill out our adoption application: https://www.dayofthedogs.org/adoption-application

- one of our team members will get back to you. 

- our dogs can be seen by appointment only after an approved application has been received.

- Adoption fee is $460. This helps to cover her spay(which will be scheduled in a month due to age), initial vaccines, rabies, initial worming, and microchip.

-We cannot place holds on our dogs. Please do not contact us until you are prepared to adopt.

NOTE:  We are very good about updating the pet's profiles once adopted.  So no need to write us to ask "Is he/she still available?"  If the post is up, the dog is still available. 

About Us:
Day of the Dogs is a 501c3 nonprofit that is dedicated to helping shelters increase live release.  We coordinate 2 - 4 transports per month from TX, OK and AR to NW Indiana/Chicagoland area.  We do direct adoptions ourselves out of Dyer, IN area and partner with 12 other rescues and shelters in both IL and IN that are willing to help southern pets in need.   
We rely on donations to help fund our ongoing transports.  Please donate if you can.  Every dollar adds up and we are grateful for any help we can get: https://www.paypal.com/paypalme/DayoftheDogs

animal.description: Sweet Emma didn’t have the best start to life. She was kept in a kennel that was way too small for her and starved. A neighbor saw her one day and took her to the shelter for help. That’s when Emma’s life took a turn for the better. Emma was only 11 lbs when Cypress Lucky Mutt Rescue picked her up from the shelter. She is now over 40 and just BEAUTIFUL! Emma needs a home with someone who has time to exercise  with her. She LOVES everything! All dogs, cats and humans... She will do best in a home with a big yard and another dog. She is timid at first but warms up easily. Emma is fully vetted, 1.5 year old, 42 lbs and a goof ball! Please give Emma a chance, she really deserves a loving home!

animal.description:
Oggie is a big ball of love! 

Ogden was dumped in a small community close to Texarkana, TX. Oggie is being fostered by the family where he was dumped. He is a bit too active for this family's senior dogs so he is looking for a new home. 

Oggie loves getting out of his kennel to run and play with another large neighborhood female stray. When foster mom is home from work, she and Oggie play fetch, a game she says he really enjoys. Oggie is a sweet boy who would love being part of an active family. He is too energetic for families with small children or elderly members because he has a habit of jumping up on people. Foster mom is working on breaking that habit, but further training will likely be required in his new family. 

Foster mom says Oggie is very sweet and loving and sometimes he will howl ""I love you"". Oggie is working on leash training but has a bad habit of pulling on leash especially when he first comes out of his kennel. Oggie would love a fenced yard where he could run and play and expend some energy or maybe a family who runs on a regular schedule.



Name: Ogden Oggie
Breed: Rottweiler mix
Sex: Male
Age: 1 1/2 years old
Weight: 61 pounds
Spayed/Neutered: Yes
Vaccinations: Up to date
Heartworm: Negative 
Microchipped: Yes

BASED ON OUR OBSERVATIONS: 
Good with Children: Over 12
Good with Dogs: Yes- has not lived with other dogs but does well with them outside. 
Good with Cats: Unknown

Adoption Fee: $475.00


IMPORTANT INFORMATION:
Interested in a specific dog, please fill out an application if you are interested in a dog. The number of individual inquiries is overwhelming and we are finding it difficult to respond to each one. We cannot guarantee you will receive a timely response.

Paws New England is a rescue, not a shelter, and as such we do not have our dogs housed in one location - they are in foster homes both in New England and in our southern foster homes. If you're interested in a specific dog, please complete a short online application and you will receive a reply within 48 hours so you can ask questions.

At present, if a dog is listed on our website, the dog is considered still available HOWEVER, may have applications that have come in before yours but it's still too early to know if any are a good match; therefore we encourage you to apply.


NOTICE WITH REGARD TO LOCATION OF DOGS: Please note: Paws New England is a foster-based rescue. We do not have a brick and mortar building to house the dogs we rescue. We have found that dogs in foster homes are much more adoptable because they have been observed in a home setting. Dogs listed with Paws New England typically reside in various locations throughout the south (primarily Tennessee, Texas, and Arkansas) and New England (not necessarily in the state of Rhode Island). You will be notified by the adoption coordinator of the location of the dog you are interested in so you have the ability to decide whether to pursue adoption or not.

Dogs transported to New England are done so at a fee of $150.00 paid directly to the transporting company by Paws New England; no additional transport costs are responsibility of adopter. This fee is included in the adoption donation.

Adoption donations cover pre-adoption vet costs (including vaccinations, spay/neuter when age appropriate, and heartworm testing/treatment when necessary), a microchip, and transportation to New England if necessary.

Donations for our young, healthy puppies and dogs support their fellow canines of advanced age or suffering from injuries and abuse whose donations are reduced but whose veterinary costs are typically much higher. We appreciate your understanding that your dog will help others in need.

All known information about the animal is listed above. We do our best to give accurate information, but most of our dogs are rescues and do not come with a known history.

Paws New England abides by the dog importation regulations set forth in the states of MA, CT, NH and RI.

animal.description:
Louie Louie..oh no, you take me where you gotta go, yeah You know the song now it is time to meet Boston Buddies Louie 2.0. This super star BT came into rescue after he and his Japanese Chin sister were relinquished to a Japanese Chin Rescue group. Their previous owner who could no longer care for them didn't want to separate them since they had been together their whole lives. After several months in foster care, his foster Mom noticed the two were not really bonded. She also realized Louie had some medical issues that she was unable to address. She reached out to Boston Buddies for help. Upon taking him into rescue he was taken in for initial vetting and bloodwork. After some follow up testing it was determined that Louie has Cushing's Disease. Louie has been started on medication to control the Cushing's - they cost about $50 a month and he will need to be on the medication for his lifetime. Louie is 13 years old and weighs in at 25 pounds. Don't let his diagnosis and age discourage you. Louie 2.0 is an awesome guy! He loves other dogs, mealtime and stuffed toys! He uses the doggie door to take care of his business, is a dream on leash and never barks. Just look at those earsare they amazing or what??? Louie is neutered, up to date on all vaccines and microchipped. If you are looking to make a difference and possibly set a goal to "give back" in the new year - then pay it forward and make Louie 2.0 a member of your family. You will be rewarded 10-fold with snuggles and unconditional love! Why don't you head on over to our website and complete an adoption application
https://www.bostonbuddies.org/adoption-application/

Louie's Adoption Donation is $200.00

View more photos of Louie on our facebook page www.facebook.com/BostonBuddiesInc

animal.description:
Bluebelle is a shy girl when you first meet her. She loves to be loved on - a back scratch or belly rub will make her melt into you. Once she figures out that you're a "dog person" then she'll warm up to you. A patient owner is a must to allow her to build her confidence. So many things are still new to her so she needs a person to introduce her to all the fun things in life.

She loves to ride shotgun in the car and sits there like a patient passenger asking "where are we going?". Mostly she just wants to be with her humans. She enjoys a hike in the woods and will try to smell every single blade of grass along the way. She's a strong walker for such a little dog so a harness works best to keep her comfy and nearby.

Her favorite spots in the house are either on the couch or sitting on the rug in front of the 'treat room'. She's loving the good life! When she's not sleeping her little feet are in constant motion because she's just so excited about all the possibilities for fun things to happen.

She hasn't had a single accident in the house, has mastered the doggie door, and can be crated overnight or while you are out. When left alone in the house she might drag something around the house (a box, your socks, a leash) but hasn't shown any destructive nature at all. Bluebelle has a big bark but she only barks with purpose to sound the alarm. She won't be bothering the neighbors!

She loves bones but hasn't shown a lot of interest in toys yet. She will also carry her food bowl around - even if it's full - so you might end up with kibble on the couch. She can be a silly girl!

A securely fenced yard is a must because she is a fast runner and could chase a squirrel into the next county before you know it. She's shown no sign of trying to jump or dig her way out, but given the opportunity of an open gate she would take it.

Because of her limited vision, she will pull away if you approach her quickly from her blind side so be patient with her. It's important that she be introduced slowly to new people. She'll go at her own pace and having her trusted human alongside her will make it easier. Some sniffs and a scratch behind the ears are a great introduction.

She isn't suitable for a home with young children or with a super-playful dog, but she lives in her foster home with two older and larger dogs and has been fine once they got to know each other. Upon meeting cats she notices them but hasn't otherwise interacted. She would do fine as an only pet but would need to meet any other family pets to make sure they are a match.

This little girl will be so loyal to her forever human and is a happy and loving companion ready to join you on any adventure. Bluebelle is ready to see the world with you!

animal.description:
Noel is a very, very sweet 3 to 4 year old purebred, 26 pound chocolate tri Beagle girl but was very timid and afraid when she first came into rescue, in large part because she had to be humanely trapped in order to be caught. Very thin when we got her with ribs showing, Noel obviously has suffered neglect for some time.  She is making great progress thanks to her loving caregivers, but hugely because of our Lily Beagle, also posted on our Petfinder page, who has been such a blessing to Noel. Playful, friendly, and loving Lily has befriended Noel and has helped her make great strides in her socialization and trust of others. We would love to find a loving home for Noel where she would have a doggie sibling. 

Dr. Ginny did confirm that Noel is heartworm positive, but the good news is that Noel tested negative for the tickbourne diseases and does not have a fever. She received heartworm preventative and  a dose of flea and tick prevention, and best of all, her bloodwork looked great! 

Her ears are very, very infected, also from neglect, but we are all over that, cleaned them and packed them with medication, and will recheck with another ear cytology in a couple of weeks and see what else may be needed for her ear care. And true to her Beagle breed, she eats every single bite of her meals. She even was given some home cooked chicken treats for Christmas, as you can see in her video. What more could a Beagle girl want for Christmas! 

I was able to spend time with Noel recently, and she is already filling out well and looking amazingly well in spite of all the former neglect. The clinic staff absolutely love her. As soon as Dr. Ginny feels Noel is healthy enough to withstand surgery, she will be spayed, and a plan for heartworm treatment will be put into place. Noel is a gem of a Beagle girl and deserves only the very best. We intend to see that she gets just that.

The only applications we are accepting for Noel at the present time are from families who are interested in fostering-to-adopt. Our Hayley is presently in such a home and doing great with her heartworm treatment. Her foster family tells us what a great bonding experience it is to be such an integral part of her journey to wellness. They LOVE her! We want the same for Noel—to be able to go into a loving home, just as soon as her doctors think she is ready, and who would like to be a part of Noel’s  journey to wellness and eventually be her forever home. If you think you are the right family for Noel and are willing to be a part of her journey to wellness, please contact Diana at dmoore2003@bellsouth.net. We are very interested in talking to you and meeting you.

Please visit also our rescue Facebook page where we post updates, pictures, and videos of all of our dogs, including Noel. Petfinder limits us on the number of pictures and videos we can post, but Facebook does not.

We should tell you that our Beagles are highly sought and adopted quickly after vetting. Fostering to adopt Noel would give you as her foster through heartworm treatment the very first to have the option of adopting her. Fostering would put you at the top of the adoption list for her.

animal.description:
Meet Todd!

This spunky guy is looking for his forever home. Todd is roughly 3 years old, neutered, and ready to find his family. Todd was brought in as a stray, so unfortunately we do not know much about his history.
Todd needs a family who is prepared for his energy, and ready to help him with some obedience. Todd has a lot of energy, and will need to be exercised daily. He enjoys running, and playing with his toys outside. 
Due to the cattle dog in Todd, he does have some tendency to nip. We have been working with Todd on this, and rewarding him when he is calm and focused.
Todd will need some assistance learning manners, but he is definitely a people pleaser. Todd loves snuggles, and is treat motivated, which will help his training. Todd does not do well with cats, and we aren't quite sure how he will get along with other dogs. We will require a dog introduction at HSoP if you have another dog in your home. All adoptions come with a seven-day foster period, to ensure the adoption is a good fit for all.

If you are interested in meeting Todd, please call us at (208)883-1166 to schedule an appointment.

animal.description:
Ginger is a beautiful and loving 7-8 year old, 60lb shepherd mix who loves chasing balls, tugging on ropes and slowly chewing the squeakers out of every toy she’s ever had!  She knows how to sit, but is still working on sitting calmly for any time. She loves walks, is learning to heel, and to stop when her human stops. She’s crate trained, and views her crate as a “happy place” for sleeping or relaxing.

Ginger needs to be the only pet in her new home, as she doesn’t get along with other dogs or small animals.  And because she can sometimes react out of fear when startled, and is protective of her food, we’re also recommending no small children in her home.

This girl has a loving heart, and in the right home with people who understand that both patience and gentle discipline are needed, she will continue to blossom.

If you feel your home might be the right place for such a great dog - the place to start is with the adoption application found at www.dfwrescueme.org/adopt.  Once submitted, the foster will contact you promptly to tell you more and to arrange a time to meet!

The adoption fee for all of our dogs is $250.00, which includes their vaccinations and spay/neuter.

Ginger is participating in the DFW Rescue Me Guest Dog Program, so ongoing care and custody are provided by their foster, not by DFWRM.

animal.description:
If you are interested in any of the dogs available at New Leash Rescue, you can reach out to the foster listed below for more information and then complete an adoption application which can be found at https://www.newleashrescue.org/adopt/policy.  Please email the completed application to newleashrescue2018@gmail.com

This pup and his siblings came to us back in early October from a reservation in South Dakota. The pups were scared and hadn't received a lot of human socialization, but they have had some good time to warm up to things in their foster home to change that.

The pups will be medium sized dogs, and are around 30 pounds currently. They are estimated to be around six months old. Their breed is completely an estimate based off appearance.  Maybe some lab, or husky in there (the blue eyes on some.)

The pups will do best in a home with older kids age 9 and up, as they will be a little shy. They will do best with families who are willing to give them the time and patience to warm up to a new home, and slowly continue to expose them to new people and situations to continue improving their socialization.  Jack Skeleton will hide when first meeting new people and will need to warm up.  He's such a sweet boy. 

These pups have lived with other dogs and cats to this point, and they do not live with small children. The pups will need refreshers on house training, and will need to continue to work on obedience and leash training.  They have been living with a fenced in yard since coming to rescue.  

Applications are reviewed in the order received looking for a right fit home.

Adoption fee is $400 + tax (no checks)

Foster to contact: Darla - foliagepeeps@yahoo.com or 612.202.5243

Please contact the foster if you are interested in learning more about this pup. An approved adoption application is needed for any meet and greets. 

Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home. An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home. 

Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home and truly become comfortable. There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption, discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, and 3 months. We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.

If you are interested in any of the dogs available at New Leash Rescue, you can reach out to the foster listed below for more information and then complete an adoption application which can be found at https://www.newleashrescue.org/adopt/policy.  Please email the completed application to newleashrescue2018@gmail.com

This pup and her siblings came to us back in October from a reservation in South Dakota.  The pups were very scared and hadn't received a lot of human socialization, but they have had some good time to warm up to things in their foster home.  

Pumpkin is the most shy and timid pup of her litter.  She can be protective of food and toys around her siblings.   She is very cuddly and loving with her foster mom, but she is scared of men.  She would need men who are super patient and willing to go slow with her to earn her trust.   Pumpkin will prefer the women in her home.   Pumpkin will hide when people first meet her and she needs time to warm up. 

The pups will be medium sized dogs, and are around 30 pounds currently.  They are estimated to be around six months old.  Their breed is completely an estimate based off appearance.   

The pups will do best in a home with older kids age 9 and up, as they will be a little shy.  They will do best with families who are willing to give them the time and patience to warm up to a new home, and slowly continue to expose them to new people and situations to continue improving their socialization.    

These pups have lived with other dogs and cats to this point, and they do not live with small children.   The pups will need refreshers on house training, and will need to continue to work on obedience and leash training.  

Applications are reviewed in the order received looking for a right fit home.  

Adoption fee is $400 + tax (no checks) 

Foster to contact:  Darla - foliagepeeps@yahoo.com or 612.202.5243

Please contact the foster if you are interested in learning more about this pup.  An approved adoption application is needed for any meet and greets.  

Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home. An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home. 

Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home and truly become comfortable. There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption, discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, and 3 months. We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.
