animal.description:
Beautiful Bella, a Catahoula leopard dog mix, is currently being fostered in Clearwater, FL (Pinellas County). Bella was surrendered by her owner at 6 months of age and was rescued from a Tennessee shelter in December at 8 months. She still has a lot of puppy in her and will not fully mature until 2 years of age. In spite of being surrendered so young, she knows her name and some basic commands (sit, off, lie down), and she is potty trained.

Bella is a busy bee and requires a lot of exercise and stimulation. If left unattended or crated for extended periods, Bella becomes distressed and nervous, which manifests in destructive chewing indoors and hole-digging outdoors. Bella will do best in a home with a high level of activity, with at least 2-3 hours of exercise and play each day. Crate time should be 4 hours or less, daily.

Bella never met a stranger - she is very social with other dogs and people, even when on leash. She loves to run in open spaces and will enjoy the companionship of another active dog who likes to play chase and wrestle. Her herding tendencies do come out in play, so if overexcited she can nip or get "mouthy," but responds to an appropriate reprimand to settle down. Bella is friendly to kids ages 5+ and will fetch a ball and play tug o' war. She loves her chew toys and puzzle toys with food rewards. While she hasn't had an opportunity to go swimming during her foster stay, she does seem interested in the pool and enjoys walking on the beach and looking for interesting things to chew.

Obedience training will help Bella learn her boundaries. She loves to take walks on the leash but her strong prey drive can make her unruly when she spots squirrels or rabbits. She is responding to positive reinforcement training on the leash but consistency and additional training will really help her develop. With work, she could become a great running buddy.

Bella is spayed, with no known medical issues, and is current with all shots for her age. She requires a home with a fenced-in yard and another active dog to play with.

Meet Boone, a one and a half year old Retriever/Chow mix.

Boone is a big bold weighing in at 77 pounds. He is strong and does pull on his leash when out walking, so a harness might be best moving forward to teach him some leash manners. He loves running around in off-leash areas and does calm down after a few minutes of fetch before he lays down to chew on a toy. Boone loves to play and is very happy, he was rolling around in the snow during the photoshoot and won us all over. He really is a silly, outgoing boy who would love a family to call his own.

If you are interested in adopting this pet please fill out an adoption questionnaire at www.yakimahumane.org. A Yakima Humane Society staff member will contact you once your questionnaire has been received.

If you would like to adopt this pet you can fill out an online adoption form at www.yakimahumane.org. Please give the name and ID number for the animal you wish to adopt.
If you are thinking about adding a pet to your family, be a hero, please consider adopting a shelter pet and if you already have pets – for life’s sake – spay and neuter. Spaying and neutering your pets is the single most important thing you can do to help decrease our nations severe pet overpopulation.
*NOTE: Nearly 90% of the animals that come into our shelter are abandoned, neglected, traumatized, injured, or ill. We attempt to give our best assessment of the animal’s welfare and temperament. Unfortunately, due to lack of funding, volunteers, and resources our physical and mental assessment of the animal is not always 100% correct.

animal.description:
American Bulldog/Pitty Mix |  Male | 3 years | 70 lbs | Adoption Fee $250

Requirements: Previous Large Breed Experience

Rudy is a giant sweetie with a big heart. He found himself in a Chicago shelter without the words to explain the history behind the scars on his chest and tears in his ear. Rudy shows his gratitude for the home life by exchanging kisses for pets and being eager to please. He loves to play with all sorts of toys - stuffed, rope, food dispensing, or chew toys. He loves to be near his humans and is content to lay on a dog bed near you, however, he is also just fine being alone.

Rudy has a medium - high energy level. He needs mental enrichment and decent exercise if he is to lounge the rest of the day. When he's excited, he likes to sloppily spin in circles and throw play bows. It's quite entertaining, however, he could potentially knock over or step on small kids or pets. He rarely jumps on humans or furniture, but he will occasionally jump up if very excited. He responds immediately to any sort of vocal no marker ("eh-h" or "uh-uh"). Rudy enjoys walks and does well walking in a front clip harness / martingale collar combo.

Rudy is crate trained (he even tries to squeeze into any small crate where a door is left open) and is working on potty training. He is doing very well not pottying in the house as long as he is taken outside frequently while loose in the house.

Rudy has many scars on his ears and legs from scuffles with other dogs; however, he's been happy to see every dog he's met so far in rescue. He is a big, strong boy, so he intimidates some dogs and needs to be reminded to play gently at times. He has not been introduced to cats yet, but he does ignore the small caged pets in his foster home.

If you are looking for a strong, large best friend to go on adventures with, then apply today to learn more!

animal.description:
The application is the first step in the adoption process, so if you are interested in adopting please fill out the online adoption application first by visiting our website at www.dachshundpaws.org

****Special Needs**** Luna is a 3 year old, tweenie sized Dachshund. Luna is a beautiful girl. Luna weighs about 16 pounds. Luna is a special girl! Luna came to us from South Korea. She is a double dapple, which is very bad breeding practice. Most double dapples have some sort of health impairments. Luna is blind. Don't tell Luna though, she gets along very well. She uses her little nose to help guide her.
Luna came in from South Korea completely fearful and scared. I am sure being blind and all the changes she went through, was very hard on her. Once she calmed down and decompressed, her true personality emerged. Luna is a love bug!!! She loves to play with toys, loves attention and even gives wonderful kisses. Luna gets along great with other dogs and would probably do best with a friendly dog in the home to help her get along. Luna enjoys her little yard. She likes to sunbathe and explore. She is good with walks and is all around a happy girl.
Luna does need a couple days when in her new home to adjust. She will be very fearful and timid. Her reaction to fear is fear biting, so she does need a patient family that will allow her to come out of her shell on her own. Luna's ideal home would be someone not gone long hours, has a friendly/playful doggie sibling and absolutely no children. Luna is extremely special and is looking for an equally as special family to call her own.
Luna came to us from South Korea and is ready to start his new life with a wonderful family. All of the dogs but 1 were positive for heart worm in South Korea when we started this process. We mentioned it multiple times. They all received aggressive treatment in South Korea. The vets there treat heart worm daily, so this is a normal treatment to them. It is standard procedure to retest for heart worm in 3 months just to be on the safe side.
Heart worm is not only common in South Korea but also in many states in the U.S. We are just fortunate to live in a climate here in California where heart worm is not prominent.
The organization in South Korea that we worked with on this project has brought over 400 dogs to the states and none have re tested positive for heart worm. They are very successful treating it.
We stand behind our dogs and should someone adopt one of the South Korea rescues from us, retest in 3 months, and by some chance the dog comes up positive for heart worm, we will pay to have the dog treated. But, we are very confident this will not be the case.
Luna's adoption fee: $200We do not have a kennel or facility to visit, all dogs are kept in foster homes until their forever homes are found.Adoption Process: Once an approved application is on file, we will then set up a home visit. At that time we will bring the dog to the home in which you will all be sharing. We ask the entire family to be there that day. If we all agree on the placement, then the dog will stay with you that day. Please visit our website at www.dachshundpaws.org

Odin is estimated to be a lab mix pup born around 9/10/20.    The pups came to us from a reservation in SD.  Odin and his sibling were seen being dumped from a vehicle and a good samaritan helped to catch the pups and get them to safety.  When they came to rescue, they had mange and bad secondary skin infections.  They have been receiving care and treatment since November, and it's now time for them to look for homes of their own.  

The pups can be protective of resources around other dogs and will still need work on this.  They do fine with people taking things away from them.  This is common when pups come from conditions where they weren't getting everything they need, and they need families committed to helping them along with this.   They currently live with children and are doing well, but would be recommended with dog savvy children. 

The pups are curious and love to explore.  They live with other dogs and are doing well.  They are working on house training and will continue to need training including obedience and leash training.   The pups are active and playful but also love to be with their people and snuggle.    They have not been exposed to cats in their foster home.  

Odin is currently being treated for an ear infection, and his adopter will need to be willing to take on the followup for that, as well as the remaining vetting he will need as a pup to finish his series.  

Adoption applications are reviewed in the order received looking for the a good fit home.      

Adoption fee is $475.00 + tax (no checks)

Astrid and her brother Odin were seen being dumped from a vehicle and a good samaritan helped to catch the pups and get them to safety.  When they came to rescue, they had mange and bad secondary skin infections.  They have been receiving care and treatment since November, and it's now time for them to look for homes of their own.  

The pups can be protective of resources around other dogs and will still need work on this.  They do fine with people taking things away from them.  This is common when pups come from conditions where they weren't getting everything they need, and they need families committed to helping them along with this.   They currently live with children and are doing well, but would be recommended with dog savvy children. 

The pups are curious and love to explore.  They live with other dogs and are doing well.  They are working on house training and will continue to need training including obedience and leash training.   The pups are active and playful but also love to be with their people and snuggle.    They have not been exposed to cats in their foster home.  

Adoption applications are reviewed in the order received looking for the a good fit home.      

Adoption fee is $475.00 + tax (no checks) 

Foster to contact: Amanda at tuszynski24@gmail.com

Please contact the foster to learn more about this pup. 

Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home. An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home. 

Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home and truly become comfortable. There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption, discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, and 3 months. We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.

animal.description:
This toy-loving handsome hunk is Titus, a 13 year old Pit mix in need of a new home through no fault of his own. Although he weighs about 80 lbs, Titus as a delicious mush of a pup that simply wants to be loved up on. As you can see from his photos, Titus LOVES toys - the more, the merrier. Most of the time this boy is walking around with a toy in his mouth. Now he just needs to find someone to play with him.

Titus was surrendered to K9 Resorts in Fairfield, NJ, due to a family member's allergies. While K9 Resorts is a clean, beautiful, loving facility, it is not meant to be a permanent home for dogs, especially a senior dog that deserves all the love and attention one can offer. Whether this is with a "foster" family, an adoptive parent, or a senior sanctuary, we would love to find a caring home for this sweet boy.

In his former home, Titus lived with another dog years ago. In recent years he has had no contact with other dogs so if a prospective adopter has a dog, a meet & greet between the dogs will be necessary. Cats are an unknown. He walks well on a leash & we haven't witnessed him reacting to other dogs when he is on leash.

Titus is good with everyone he meets & has lived with a child for years but he'd probably do best with kids older than toddler age because of his size. He is up to date on his vaccines and has no bite history - he's just an all-around great guy! Titus does not have as much energy as he once did and behaves well with the staff at K9 Resorts. He does have some arthritis in his hind legs which makes him a little unsteady on wet, slippery surfaces. Otherwise, he seems to be in perfect health.

Titus walks very nicely on a leash. He is rather goofy in the car & needs a seat belt. He doesn't quite "get" what being in a car is. Toys? Titus LOVES toys... he's super good with toys! The more, the better!

Titus is NOT with Eleventh Hour Rescue but we are helping to network him for placement. If you are interested in helping Titus find a wonderful retirement home, please contact Anna of K9 Resorts directly at 201-982-4309 (cell) or 973-244-7387 (office). If you prefer email please write to fairfield@k9resorts.com.

Thank you for your consideration of Titus' situation - those of us that know & love this guy just want him happy & safe & settled!

Frankie is a little over a year old, and has been neutered. microchipped, vaccinated, and is current on parasite prevention. animal.description:
Hello all, you may remember me as the skinny furless dog from a couple months ago. Well would ya look at me now... They're calling me a polar bear cause I'm so big and fluffy!

Let's see, what else has changed between then and now... Oh yeah, I have so much more energy now. I still love to cuddle but gotta say I really enjoy romping around most of the day! I love to wrestle with my foster brothers but I also love one on one attention from my foster parents through playtime and runs. Having a doggie sibling would be nice but as long as I'm taken to doggie daycare or on play dates I will be just fine as the only dog in the household.

Things I love: fetch, squeaky toys, petting my humans to ask for more pets in return, wrestling, running, and everything else that is fun!

I'm a big strong girl and I need a family that can handle me with ease. Don't let my size completely fool you though, I'm still a puppy learning a lot of things and it's hard for me not to just goof off sometimes. I'm very smart and know basic commands, I am also potty- and crate-trained. Regular exercise and play will be a necessity for me as I love being active. I am looking for a home with a yard to run and play in.

animal.description:
Floki is a 1-2 year old, 70 pound, Walker Coonhound who was brought to us by animal control. He was previously an outdoor dog so he will need quite a bit of training and time to acclimate to living in a house. He is a very energetic and vocal dog who loves to run. He needs some leash training as his nose is always to the ground, searching for animals in the woods - like a typical hunting dog!
Floki is very friendly but may have had some previous, negative interactions with other dogs, so he does like getting too close. He also seems to want to chase cats so he will need to be an only pet for a while until he has had some socialization. He does have a tendency to get mouthy, grabbing on to shirt sleeves when he is frustrated and not 'working.'
With some time, exercise, and training, we think that Floki will be a great addition to an active family.Please visit the following link on our website to learn about Second Chance's adoption process. http://www.2ndchanceanimalcenter.org/adoption.html

animal.description:
Amari is a beautiful 3-year old pocket Belgian Malinois located in California. Amari is a tri-pod having landed in a shelter with severe injuries to her right front leg. Unable to save it, the leg was amputated, but that hasn't slowed Amari down one bit! 

Amari is a shy gal that warms up with happy talk and yummy treats. Once comfortable she runs laps around you, even though she's missing a leg! Amari has your typical Belgian Malinois traits: she has high energy, high prey drive, is very active, and wants a job to do. She loves going for walks, chewing on bones and playing with puzzle toys, anything to keep her occupied! When done she loves to curl up and get cozy with her favorite people.

She can be nervous when by herself in a new environment where she's shown some mild destructive behavior (mainly chewing) but this subsides when getting comfortable in a home. She's also an escape artist, so proper enclosures are a must. It's recommended that she is given time to transition into a new home and given plenty of physical exercises and mental enrichment, as well as crate and obedience training. As a tripod, she would do best with exercises that strengthen her legs - minimal jumping, lots of swimming, short walks to slowly build stamina. She's getting stronger every week! Ideally, her home consisted of few stairs.

Amari can be pushy with some dogs and will need proper introductions. She resource guards food and toys with other dogs but not with her humans. She does better with mellow male dogs. She doesn't quite understand when another dog doesn't want to play and takes what she wants (toys, food).

This little gal has been through a lot and needs a home that will give her time to adjust and help her work through the transition. She really dislikes furry balls aka cats. Ideally she'll go to a home where she's the only pet, but she can live harmoniously with other dogs.

Amari is a true Velcro dog and would love to go wherever you go! 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering this pet, please complete an application at this link https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/24689/generic . 

We are an official 501C3 organziation that does not have a physical location. Our home address is in Michigan, however, the majority of our dogs are not located in Michigan. The physical location of each of our dogs is posted with the name of the pet or in the title area. If you are within 4 hours of the pet, please be prepared to pick the pet up. We do provide transport assistance, however, the applicant must drive 50% of the total distance of the transport. 

The information that we have available is in our posting. If you would like to discuss this animal additionally please fill out this application. Applications that are completed in our process and being considered as a match will speak to the foster home to gain more information about our adoptable dog. 

If you have questions about this pet please contact us at info@MADrescueinc.org. 

You may also call our toll free number at 844-MAD-RESQ or 844-623-7377. 

Additional information about all of our dogs for adoption can be located at our website MAD Rescue Inc

animal.description:
Zoey is full of life! Social butterfly with people and dogs alike. She loves being the life of the party & wants to mingle with everyone whether at home or the dog park.

She loves to be outdoors! Explore, play, walk, run, swim, you name it! Loves the water & could give anyone a run for their money in a race whether on land or in water. Needs a home with a fenced in yard or on a farm so she can be outside & run to her hearts desire. 

Lazy is not in her DNA, literally. Mainly Mountain Cur in makeup she is a working dog & thrives on giving her a job. Great treeing instincts and would love being on a farm or hunting. Very smart & picks up new skills quickly- she was treadmill trained in minutes. Yes, you read that right... She runs on the treadmill! :)

Highly food motivated & hasn't met a toy she didn't like. She loves food & her toys so much she tends to guard them & needs to be only dog in the home. Active dog by day, but cuddler by night... When 8pm hits she is ready to lay with you on the couch & cuddle until it's time to go to bed in her cage. 

Potty and crate trained. Spayed, chipped & up to date on all shots. Embark DNA test results done so you know her exact breed make up. 

Apply www.fourleggedranch.com

animal.description:
Meet Abby! This pretty Pitbull mix is on the lookout for her forever family! Abby is an energetic, athletic girl who loves to run and play with her people. She would make the perfect hiking companion for weekends out on the trails, and enjoys frequent jogs around the neighborhood park. Her gregarious, friendly personality ensures she makes new friends everywhere she goes! 

Abby enjoys the company of other dogs as well, and happily romps around with her canine friends in playgroups at the shelter. She is currently living in a foster home with another dog, and gets along famously with her. She would love to have a doggie friend in her forever home to romp around with each day. Her foster also takes her on frequent field trips to the dog park where she has a blast socializing with everyone she meets! 

Abby is a wonderful companion in the house, and has great house manners. She sleeps loose in her foster's home overnight, and is quiet until morning. She is already potty trained, and is crate trained. Abby rides very well in the car, but she is still working a bit on her leash manners. She has met younger children previously, and is gentle and kind with them. 

After a long day of fun in the great outdoors, Abby happily spends her nights snuggled up with her humans on the couch watching Netflix. This sweet girl will make a fantastic companion for whichever family is lucky enough to adopt her. If Abby sounds like a good fit for your household, schedule an adoption appointment today!

He’s a active boy with lots of energy so he would benefit off a active home he can get daily exercise. He need someone who can work with him and continue his training. When we rescued him from the shelter he was scared of everything and he has come a long way! Comet is very playful and loves his toys! He tends to stay to himself most of the time and rather be around his dog friends than people.
He’s not a dog that really wants to cuddle up on the couch. Comet loves other dogs but can be a bit awkward so a compatible friend would be best! 

Comet is a 3 year old pit bull mix around 60 lbs. Beautiful white come with black spots! He is a sweet boy that deserves the best home. He’s been neutered, chipped, fully vaccinated, and current on flea meds. We do prefer a home without small animals and small children. If you are interested in meeting Comet please send us a detailed email and request a application to fill out. 

We do require home owners only with a fully fenced in yard at least 6 feet. Bully breed experience is a must. We are located in Northern California and adopt out locally. We need to be close enough for a home checks and meets.

Hemi is a 7-9 year old 75-80 lb Anatolian Shepard.  
- He is very healthy, good natured and likes humans! 
- He probably would be good with kids and he seems to be good with passive dogs (a female border collie, plays with male Husky - see video) but is selective.   
- He loves being outdoors!   Even when left alone he won’t try to jump or climb the fence, he doesn’t dig or jump at the fence.  He does like to bark at distractions and also scratches the ground when excited but easy around people, doesn’t jump up on people.  
- He is leery of being pet directly on top of the head but likes ear & neck rubs and will be your best friend for hours if you scratch his butt !!  :)    
- He doesn’t seem to be in to fetch but loves tug-of-war with people.  
- He is very gentle taking treats.
- He knows SIT very well and catching on to DOWN quickly.  
- He walks fairly well on a leash when no distractions. 
 - He seems perfectly happy to be outside (even alone) but might have separation anxiety when left alone inside.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Tikaani is a very special boy - he came to us at GPRM but went straight to the wonderful fosters who have worked with him from day one. He has made remarkable progress - but he still has more to learn and will only be adopted to a very Pyr savvy adopter willing to put in the time and effort. This is what the foster mom says:

Tikaani (Kaani) is a 2-year-old pocket pyr" at only 65 pounds, but he makes up for his lack of size with his extra-large personality. He is very in tune with his people, extremely intelligent, and needs to be challenged.

Tikaani had a very rough start to life, and will require and deserves an extra special home. He came in to rescue at only 8 months old, and we were given little to no information about what to expect. We immediately found out he is extremely nervous around new people, and it takes a lot of time and patience to earn his trust.

He bonds hard to the people he trusts, and like a typical pyr, he can be very protective. He does not like new people in the home, but he does warm up after frequent, repeat visits-and very slow introductions. He has the most expressive, captivating eyes, and if you pay attention, you can always tell what he needs.

His front right leg is shorter than the others due to previous mistreatment. He has been through testing and therapy and it doesn't seem to cause him any pain, but it is a constant, visual reminder of why he fears humans.

He loves car rides, walks, puzzle toys, and spending time with his humans. Kaani is a goofy, playful, silly boy who never fails to make me laugh. He likes to "jaw snap" (make a barking motion without any noise) when he's excited or just wants to talk back-we often have conversations back and forth. While he's not much of a snuggler, he always likes to be close and makes me feel so incredibly loved. I've spent time with a lot of dogs over the years, and none have given me the sweet, devoted feeling he does.

Tikaani requires an experienced pyr owner with a lot of patience, love, and understanding. His ideal home would be a quiet home with no children, few visitors, and with adults who can meet him where he is and work at his pace. He's the pyrfect dog for any introvert! He would do best with a female dog around the same age, and he is great with cats/kittens. 1/31/21 2:42 PM
animal.name: Takaani (was Carlos)

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.As is the usual, Anubis was brought to us through no real fault of his own.

Nubis (Noobis)

Noobis is more of a person than a dog. He responds to conversation and talking more than he responds to commands. Some wonderful qualities of Noobis are his intelligence, his loyalty, and his regal dignity.

He is somewhat socially awkward with other dogs, as he doesn't seem to have been raised around any other animals, in addition raised in a somewhat controlled environment (not a lot of early socialization.) So, when he plays he opens his mouth, but then never closes it, and he doesn't really know how to "play." He can tell that you are excited, and you would like to play with him, however, he looks at you as if you are just doing a funny dance. It can look a little awkward, and that is the many things we love about him. He is being fostered with another large dog, cats, rabbits, and ducks. He initially was interested if they wanted to challenge him to a staring contest, and once that was off the table, he was not interested anymore. He is fine with the other animals, but don't expect him to interact with them. He is kind of a stay at home and read a book with his family next to the fire dog person.

He is a light eater, and loves to have his tummy rubbed. He does protect his home to an extent, but he will obey you if he feels like it. Often I have had to walk to him to ask him to come inside. He knows I am talking to him, again, that intelligence thing, and beautiful Pyrenees thing.

I think a home that is fairly calm with lower expectations of needing a "get excited and run around dog" would be a great home. A home that is willing to laugh at his quirks, honor his intelligence, and uphold his dignity. He loves car rides, walks with his human. He is very expressive with his body, and is always curious in a gentle way.

Noobis would ultimately like a quiet home with very little stimulation (preferably not right in town). He has no interest in other dogs or animals and prefers the company of his humans.

Noobis has not been previously socialized and is very scared and reactive to new situations, people at the door, and barks at people when in the car. He responds according to his scared feelings with reactive barking and lunging at other people and dogs when on a walk. As he gains more exposure and confidence, these behaviors are subsiding. However, he will need continued training, positive reinforcement, confidence building and a calm voice at all times to continue his rapid improvement. Previous Pyr experience is required

If you are interested in learning more about this boy, please reach out. We are anxious to find him the Pyrfect forever home.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Banjo has been fostered in Utah where he was learning how to get along with canine housemates as well as people. He is a beautiful dog, quite large, with a lot to learn yet - will definitely need to go to someone willing to continue his training.

This is what his foster mom just told us:

This guy, Banjo has come so far in the last few months. He was terribly insecure and would go after our dogs. He broke a choke chain, chewed through so much stuff and had no manners at 100lbs and only 10 months. I truly didn't know if we could help him.

Banjo is a COMPLETELY different dog now. Still a puppy at almost 12 months so he needs constant reminders that the rules are still in place. He is an amazingly sweet boy who loves people and especially kids. I thought once he was unadoptable, but with a few months of hard work on our and his part he is ready to adopted. This is why we foster. It's hard work, lots of tears, and some incredibly difficult and exhausting days, but watching Banjo just become a dog is the best thing ever.

He will need an owner that is familiar and confident with the Great Pyrenees breed.

*********************

These comments are directly from the foster mom and great information for potential adopters:

Crate-Trained: ABSOLUTELY NOT, he panics in the crate

Car: he is great in the car and loves to go for rides

Swim: we have no idea

Fetch: he tries but loves to get stuff to chew on

Toys: yes he loves toys

Lap: if we let him

Protective: of his people, pretty normal for the LGD's we have had

Escape: if the gate is open he will roam

Predatory: we haven't seen any of that

Obedient: he has great recall and will do almost anything for a treat. Much better than most LGD's

Playful: very, he is really rough with the other dogs but that's how they are

Timid: only with new experiences and not aggressive, he runs away

Skittish: when scared

Independent: he's a lot needier than most LGD's because of his history

Affectionate: very

Eager to please: he tries but is better with treats

Even-tempered and gentle: he is incredibly gentle with young kids we babysat for a 3, 5, 7-year-old last night and he was really good but his size scared the older boy so they were locked in the laundry room. Banjo was super upset and was way better than Sadie about the personal space and being gentle with the young kids. He does way better than a young dog should with kids.

Goofy: he is really silly and we laugh at his puppy antics

Okay with cats: Yes but will chase if they run

Great with all people may let strangers in the house if they aren't threatening

Okay with dogs: I would suggest another young LGD. He loves to play with our other 2 LGD's and they all play incredibly rough. Really it's training and it looks terrible but they are all having a great time.

LGD Experience: A must. He is entering his teen years and will need someone who knows how to continue to help him learn to be a good citizen. He does have some abandonment issues and doesn't like to be alone

Kids: He adores kids and a family would be best for him. He was around a 3-year-old and showed incredible restraint in his excitement especially for a puppy. He was not jumping on them but was so excited to be near them. Kids are a must for Banjo.

Farm animals: he is great with my geese, ducks, and goats but would need an introduction to anything else he will be homed with.

Apartment: I don't think he would be happy in an apartment setting, he loves to run and explore and play.

I would suggest Banjo go to a home with another big dog. He has shown a lot of anxiety at being alone especially outside at night. This has been lessened with the other dogs.

animal.description: SPECIAL LONG TERM/FOREVER FOSTER NEEDED OR ADOPTER. Starka is a beautiful 2 1/2 year old female Great Dane.  Unfortunately she has been diagnosed with severe dilated cardiomyopathy. The vet has given her approximately one to two years to live, but that could be shorter or longer. Hard to say.  Starka is such a sweet soul with so much love to give.  We just want to give her a chance. We are working closely with the specialist and she is on medication and the food he recommended.  The biggest issue is she cannot be put under to be spayed. When she comes into heat she is a BEAR with other female dogs, but fine with males.  It would be great to have her in a home with another male dog as she loves to play, although she has some limitations on the type and length of exercise. We understand it will be difficult to find someone to take her on knowing these issues.  If you foster her, the rescue pays all her medical bills and can provide dog food for her as well.  Boise, Idaho area preferred as that is where the specialist is located.  If interested in helping Starka, please apply at www.saintrescue.org.  All other dogs MUST be fixed. No exceptions.

animal.description:
Tallahassee gets around. He's been on city hikes, country excursions along the Katy Trail, and to a volunteer's back yard. He's walked the neighborhoods around the shelter countless times, has been out for pup cups and soft serves, and has relaxed in foster homes. He's played with other dogs in play groups and worked on his skills in the decompression room. He's welcomed new volunteers and taken long car rides. He's even begged for a Bloody Mary on a restaurant patio and was turned into a meme.
The one place Tally hasn't been since he's been in our care for the last 14 months is an adopter's home. If you can believe it, this sweet boy with elusive ears has never been adopted.
All of these adventures with numerous volunteers show how beloved Tally is. He just needs one of you to recognize what an amazing dog he is. Could it be you?

animal.description: Hi! My name is Pongo! I was rescued by the wonderful people at Big Dog Ranch from a hoarding house in Puerto Rico before arriving here at the ranch. I am a very sweet little fellow. I am so sweet that sometimes I allow my brother and some of the other dogs to pick on me. But I love to play with other dogs, regardless of their size and I think that I may even be able to live happily in a home with a feline friend. I would be a perfect fit for a first time owner with a young family looking for a forever companion. While I would love to have a big yard to play in, I think I could be comfortable in any range of living environments, including an apartment. I would prefer to live in a busy home where there are lots of things going on that I can be involved in. I love to meet new people and will always be friendly when greeting your guests. I would benefit from continued training, as I am not quite potty-trained or leash-trained yet. One of my favorite activities is playing fetch but I think the thing that I would love the most would be getting to cuddle up on the couch next to my new family forever!

animal.description:
****Please do not message the rescue asking if this dog is still available; if a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. PLEASE READ ENTIRE BIO BEFORE EMAILING****
Applicants MUST BE a minimum of 25 yrs old to ADOPT.

*Name: Esme
*Age: 1 year
*Current Weight: 48 pounds
*Rescued from: Texas
*Adoption fee: $375 (plus $125 spay/neuter deposit, which is refundable when spay/neuter agreement is fulfilled)
*Health: up to date on required vaccines


Esme is a darling dog,  She is super friendly, she has been great with all dogs that she meets and with her foster's young son.  Of course, being a year old, she is very playful and loves her toys and chasing the tennis ball in the yard.  She will need a home that currently has a fenced yard to run and explore and home with lots of love.  Esme was pulled from a high kill shelter in east Texas and is a blessed little girl to have an opportunity to find her furever home in the northeast.  If you are looking for a loving, kind, friendly girl to spoil rotten, Esme is perfect for you.

Esme was rescued from an area where there is an abundance of homeless dogs, and not a lot of shelter space for them to go while they wait for their forever homes. She will be arriving at SNARR's Adoption Center in Brewster, NY on January 23rd ready for adoption! To apply to adopt Esme, fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. 
**Meet and greets will not be scheduled without an approved application.**

IMPORTANT: This dog has not yet been altered. For any dog or puppy that is not able to be spayed/neutered prior to adoption, SNARR requires a $125 deposit in addition to your adoption fee, as well as a strictly-enforced signed Spay/Neuter Contract stating you will have this dog altered within 6 months of adoption. The $125 deposit will be returned once the contract has been fulfilled. 

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING
-------------------------------------------------------
**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
Please meet adoptable 4 – ish years old Finley.
We don’t know much about Finn’s previous life,  but when she arrived at her foster home in August she was full of fear and uncertainty.   She most likely had never seen the inside of a home,  wasn’t sure of what a leash was – hesitated to show any affection,   and has a paralyzing fear of ceiling fixtures.        Sweet Precious Finn arrived with multiple Tick borne illnesses that were to severe for antibiotics to cure on it’s own.   She must have been in so much pain,  but you would  never have known – cause thur it all Finn’s gentle and sweet spirit is unwavering.
Today – Finn has BLOSSOMED into such a wonderful companion.    Her very favorite activities are snuggling,   Bum Scratches, Playing in the snow,  eating treats and going for walks.   SERIOUSLY – Don’t even think about putting your shoes on for any other reason unless you’re ready to disappoint a tail-wagging polar bear.   
 Finley gets along with everyone,  no matter the age or species.   She rarely barks,  she walks PYRfectly on a leash,  is fully house trained,  and is just the sweetest girl EVER…   She is honestly such a terrific dog  
A few things that a forever home will need to be award of:    Because of her past,   Finn will likely need to stay on an anti anxiety medication long term (don’t worry – you can easily sneak the pills into her food) the cost is about $30.00 a month.    She requires special food to keep her bladder infections away – but it isn’t much more costly than typical premium food.   She also has a lingering fear of hard shiny floors which may resolve in time.      This was solved in her foster home with small washable throw rugs and strategically placed doggie beds/blankets.    (She has really made so MUCH progress – such an awesome girl).
. If interested in meeting Finley, please contact Sandy  or respond by e-mail -- Finley will LOVE you for it! We will also need you to fill out our adoption survey Finley will need an above ground fence for safe play and exercise. We are looking for homes in the surrounding Pittsburgh area. For more information please contact Great Pyrenees Club of Western Pennsylvania Rescue, Inc., a 501(c)(3) nonprofit rescue organization or visit our web page http://www.papyr.org for more information. Thank you for supporting animal rescue!

animal.description:
Luna is a 4 year old Dachshund/Lab Mix with a beautiful coat and a unique look.  She is long like a dachshund but has the face of a lab. Cute! Luna LOVES to be around people! She is about 40 pounds, and could stand to lose a few (we are working on it)!

Luna is a little weary of men at first, but is quick to become their best friend after making sure they are not a threat. She has yet to meet a person she is not fond of!! Although she is a lover of people she requires a home without small children 

Luna currently is being fostered with 3 other dogs of all sizes. She would do best in a home with a laid back dog or even being the only dog. Luna walks well on a leash and is getting used to being crated when her foster is not home. She is possessive of toys and food, so she is fed in her kennel as we work with her. 

Luna loves to run around outside, but is also a huge snuggler. She loves to sleep in bed with her foster at night and does so without any issues! Luna is potty trained and likes to ride in the car. A fenced in yard would be ideal for Luna.

animal.description:
3 year old Papa Bear is one of our special boys, and he's just so handsome! Short and stocky at 40lbs, he is a corgi golden retriever mix with a thick golden coat and a perfect white blaze on his face. He is vocal when happy, cuddles like a pro, loves toys, and gives the best kisses.

He has some behavioral challenges that we are confident he can overcome with the right guidance, but for this reason we will only approve applicants who are experienced with difficult dogs and who will agree to professional behavioral training. We also require a home with a fenced yard, and one without children. Please do not apply if you cannot commit to these requirements.

Papa Bear gets along with some dogs and not others, and has shown some resource guarding of toys, food, and people. We have not tested him with cats.

With people he is very wiggly, happy, and sweet 95% of the time, but will challenge and snap at his humans when he doesn't want to follow directions. He also has some car ride and leash issues that he has been working on. He will need to be sedated for vet trips and bathing, although he has learned to accept being brushed recently. 

We know the right home is out there for Papa Bear, and we are confident someone will see the good boy he is and help him become a once in a lifetime dog in his forever home.

Please fill out an application and we will call you once approved to set up a meet and greet. If you have any questions, email jessica.canineestates@gmail.com or call 908-305-9155

animal.description:
"Itchy" Echeva is a spunky, 9 year old, 14lb red chihuahua who loves food, attention, and life! He came to us from Lake County, shut down and weary of his previous life. He has mild cataracts and had severe dental disease that was treated and a large lipoma which we removed. His skin was also badly irritated from a long term flea infestation, and after some allergy injections and a few baths, it is looking much better already.

As soon as he started feeling better, this boy's personality began to shine and he really defies his age with energy and gusto. He loves affection, treats, walks well on a leash, and gets along with most dogs. He is a little grumpy and adorably confused when being picked up - he "swims" in the air with his legs! - but with practice he will be just fine. Echeva is mostly healed and will likely need some bathing and itch medication before being 100% healthy. He is ready now to find his fur-ever home, full of love, treats, and massages!

Please fill out an application and we will call you once approved to set up a meet and greet. If you have any questions, email director@canineestates.com or call 727-412-0558

animal.description:
Our very own 10 year old, 13lb, blond wire-haired dachshund mix Mick is a sweet happy boy who has been through an incredible transformation since joining the Canine Estates family two months ago.

He came to us as a stray, emaciated and unable to eat properly due to his severe dental disease. His skin and ears were so infected and raw that he was mostly bald, and his eyes were nearly glued shut. If all that wasn't enough, his bloodwork showed age-related kidney disease. Now we are two months down his road of recovery, and he is a different dog! His skin, coat, and eyes look absolutely wonderful! Though he is still taking weekly baths and some medication, he nearly done and 100% better. He eats happily after his dental with extractions, and has gained a good 3 pounds!

His kidney disease is age-related and progressive, but stable and manageable with a good vet relationship and proper diet. Due to his kidney disease, he will drink a lot and has some incontinence issues which will easily be managed with the use of belly bands and diapers.

Through all his obstacles in life, Mick has been a sweet, loving dog from day one, equally willing to amble along on an easy walk or cuddle up with his favorite humans. He gets along with other dogs, and would likely be fine with cats and respectful children as well. Mick is ready to win his way into his forever home, and we think his new family will be the real winners with this sweet boy!

Please fill out an application and we will call you once approved to set up a meet and greet. If you have any questions, email director@canineestates.com or call 727-412-0558

animal.description:
Meet SWESR’s sweet pocket senior, Han Solo. This loveable senior Setter is about 12 years old and hasn’t had the easiest life. Han’s life has taken a turn for the better since being rescued by SWESR. He’s now living in a loving foster home, getting along well with his foster dog companions, and even patrolling his new yard looking for birds and squirrels. 

Han needs a fenced yard that he can explore at his leisure and he will let you know when he is ready to come inside. He has a low prey drive and no interest in challenging a 4-foot fence. So far, Han has shown little prey drive, so he may be a candidate for a home with inside cats. 

Han is a quiet boy who may have some hearing loss, but that doesn’t keep him from being a wonderful companion. We have not had him in a home with children and we think he would prefer a quieter home with adults and possibly older children that would be gentle and not expect him to play and entertain them. He loves human attention and is a seriously “hands on” kind of Setter who enjoys lots of petting, lap time and massages. He has very few demands other than lots of love and a warm bed.

Han is house trained, crate trained, fully vetted, and currently in a foster home in Dallas TX. He is a candidate to adopt or furever foster where SWESR provides for his ongoing medical needs. He is not a candidate for flying or a volunteer transport that is more than a days drive away.

For an application to adopt or for more information about Southwest English Setter Rescue including our adoption requirements and transport availability, please go to http://www.swesr.org/. Please call us at 214-997-3885 if you have any questions.

animal.description:
Viola is a 1 year old Pit mix ready to find her forever home. She is the life of the party and would love an active family. She loves to play with other dogs, but not cats, please, as she will chase them!  She loves her people!!  If you would like it learn more about Viola, please complete an application and then reach out to Roxy@bigfluffydogs.com

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/. 

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

animal.description:
Meet Guiness!  Guiness is a two year old lab/Mastiff mix.  He spent his first few months petrified in a shelter in South Carolina after being brought in as a stray.  Slowly but surely Guiness began to come out of his shell and was sent to live with a foster family with kids and other dogs.  Although Guiness did well there, we believe he would do best in a more quiet home either as an only dog or with a confident female that he can feel secure with.
Because of his hard start in life he is shy and will need someone to show him that the world is not a scary place.  Guiness would just love to go on walks and hikes and come home to snuggle and be wrapped in a cozy blanket.  Although Guiness is a big boy, he seems to think he is a lap dog and wants to be as close as possible to his people.  Guiness is the perfect mix of active and chill.

**PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING**

If you are interested in adopting any of the puppies, our adoption fee is $495 ( puppies) $375 (adults) which includes transportation from the South and we do suggest putting a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several littermates.

**Please understand that we are a volunteer based organization. While our volunteers try to answer all emails/questions as quickly as possible, below please find answers to some of our most frequently asked questions. We ask that you please read these FAQ's to see if your question has already been answered before emailing additional questions:

- If a dog or puppy is listed on Petfinder, they are still available. Please do not email asking if they are still available. If a dog or puppy is still listed, then we are still accepting applications :-) We do not go on a first come first serve basis, but on best fit for the family and most importantly, the puppy or dog.

- We are taking our best guess on breed and size when fully-grown (or already an adult), based on the puppy's/dog’s physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. We rarely are able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. 

- Our dogs/puppies are either at our Adoption Center in Brewster, NY, in foster care, or are adopted straight from transport. An application is necessary to meet any dog/puppy. Often, dogs and puppies are spoken for before they arrive. Many people feel more comfortable with a meet and greet which we completely understand and respect, however please know you are taking a chance of that puppy/dog getting adopted by someone else before hand.

- The way to start the process for any dog or puppy is by filling out an application. Applications for foster or adoption can be found at www.snarrnortheast.org and by clicking either adopt or foster from the main menu. If you fill out an application, please make sure you answer all the questions in as much detail as possible and that you receive a confirmation email, otherwise we did NOT receive it.

animal.description:
Are any of you single ladies looking for a canine companion? Meet Miracle! Miracle is a 1 year old blue and white female pit who was released to the shelter through Oak Grove animal control because she did not like the boyfriend in the home. Miracle is very timid when meeting new people and takes a while to warm up to you and get comfortable in new surroundings. Miracle does great with the shelter staff now that she has warmed up to us although we recommend a home without children due to her history. Miracle is very selective when meeting new potential housemates and would do better in a home without other animals. Miracle is a sweet girl once given the chance and would make a great companion for any female! She is HEARTWORM NEGATIVE as of 12-18-20 and weighs about 41 pounds.

Her adoption fee is $36.50 and she can be microchipped for $8.25. Due to the outbreak of Covid-19 our adoption policies have changed. All adoptions are by appointment only. Call to set up an appointment to meet the animal. Dogs are $61.50 and puppies are $59 unless otherwise noted. All cats and kittens are $44 unless otherwise noted. Our system automatically updates petfinders every two hours. Feel free to email us with any questions you may have.

He has had three boosters and has just received the rest of his vetting which is his  rabies, micro chip, fecal, health check and neuter.

He does play very rough for his tiny self, so a stern sibling would be a good idea for him as he is dominate during play time and needs guidance.  He will chew if not supervised, of course supervising a puppy is always a must.  He is in a foster home with a cat, other dogs and horses.  A fence for outdoor supervised playtime is also required for this active baby.
His location is Chattanooga, N GA.

animal.description:
Hunter is a 9 year-old Coonhound that would love to meet you and show that he would be a great fit in your home. He's a gentle guy that will be sure to let you know when some pesky squirrels or rabbits are invading your yard, so, as with most hounds, you can expect a trademark bay. Just be sure to supervise him outside until you're confident your yard is totally secure, because he will follow his nose to wherever it may take him, and before he knows it, he won't know how to get back to his people.

He would love to find a new family in which any children are at least 16 years-old, and that understands Coonhounds like to talk, which a neighbor in an apartment, for example, may not always appreciate.

Come meet Hunter today, he'll be so excited to see you!

Everest is a mixed breed dog (no, we are not sure what she is mixed with) who is about 1 year old and weighs 40 pounds. She is a happy, active, friendly girl who still has a lot of puppy ways! She has worked hard on housetraining and almost has it down. Everest has a ton of energy and would be happiest in a home with a yard and at least one other dog to play with. She also needs basic training and a structure as she can be overwhelming when she gets too excited. Therefore, we do not think she would be great around small kids. She lives for games and toys and is super smart! She would be an excellent hiking partner and is always up for adventure! 

Augusta Dog Adoptions is an all- volunteer, foster- based rescue. We take applications online and are scheduling individual adoptions in the Waynesboro, VA area during the pandemic.  A $175.00 adoption fee ($300 for puppies under 6 months old) helps us take care of all the dogs we rescue. All dogs are spayed/neutered, tested for heartworm and tick borne diseases (if old enough), microchipped, and vaccinated for rabies (if old enough), distemper/parvo and bordetella. They are also treated for internal and external parasites. Many dogs also receive extensive medical care such as dental work and major surgeries. For more information and to apply to adopt, please visit www.augustadogadoptions.org

animal.description:
Hi, I’m Carter! I am a one year old goofy, full-of-love Black Lab and Hound mix who arrived from South Carolina just in time to celebrate the holidays with my foster family. I was a stray and very thin when I got here, but I am healthy and have been putting on weight like a champ!  I am fully housebroken, I’m doing well with crate training, and am eager to learn commands.  I am very treat motivated and my foster family has taught me off, sit, down, leave it, take it, wait, and other useful commands that help me have good behavior.  My foster family gives me lots of treats during training and I am getting really good at listening! 
 
I hope my forever home will be with an active family who has dog experience, one who gets my excitement and is eager to play with me, train me, and take me places.  I live with three boys (14,12,10) in my foster home and we have a great time together!  I hope my new home has children, but I can certainly live without children as long as I get to see them now and then when I am out.  I have played well with younger children and could probably live in a home with younger children as long as my new parents have experience managing a big confident puppy like me and my tendencies to get mouthy and sometimes treat children as my playmates.

I live with an older dog in my foster home and we do okay together, but I think I would do better with a young, active and confident canine housemate who will play with me, give me the mental stimulation I really need, and show me the ropes in my forever home.  I could also be an only dog for the right family, as long as they are committed to getting me exercise and social time with other dogs because I LOVE to play with other dogs!  I am on my best behavior at home when I get lots of  physical and mental exercise.  I haven’t been around cats so I am not sure what I think of them.

I should probably have a taller physical fence (at least 4 feet), but it's not a requirement since the backyard probably won't be my main source of exercise.  I get very excited to see people, dogs, squirrels, deer, and foxes - remember I am part Hound! - and I don’t have good recall so a fenced in yard will keep me safe.  I like to go on walks A LOT.  I do pretty well on my walks but I will pull at times when I see people, dogs, and smell other animals.  I am very friendly and want to say hi to everyone and I haven't met a dog or human I didn't like.   I am also a HUGE fan of dog parks where I can run around in big circles and have other dogs chase me.  My foster family also takes me to doggie daycare once or twice a week since my canine foster brother doesn't play with me a whole lot.  I am also a typical puppy when it comes to chewing so I need supervision to learn to chew the right things.  

I have been working so hard since I got here to be a great puppy and I can't wait to get to my forever home!

PLEASE NOTE:  While this Lab may not be available for adoption by the time you complete the adoption process, other great Labs are always finding their way into our Rescue. 

For more information on this Lab, please contact INFO@BROOKLINELABRESCUE.ORG.  

If you are interested in adopting this Lab or any other Lab from our Rescue, please visit our Web site, www.brooklinelabrescue.org, for more information on our adoption process. If you need additional information about the adoption process or whether you are in our coverage area, please send an e-mail to our Rescue at info@brooklinelabrescue.org

Even if you are not ready to adopt, you can still help us help our Labs!

Brookline Labrador Retriever Rescue is a 501(c)3 non-profit volunteer organization funded entirely by donations. Donations are always needed to help with veterinary costs, transportation, and supplies for our dogs. For information on donating to BLRR please click here. Donations are accepted via PayPal or you can mail a check to: Brookline Labrador Retriever Rescue, P.O. Box 638, Warrington, PA 18976-0638

Meet Daisy

Daisy is a gorgeous young shepherd mix at nine months old. We rescued Daisy from a high-kill shelter. We don’t know what trauma Daisy suffered, but it’s apparent that she carries some emotional baggage that we’re working to unwind. 

Since coming to us, our trainer and staff have been working with Daisy to build her confidence. She’s a gentle and timid soul. She’s not aggressive, but reticent to engage. Once she lets her guard down, she is an absolute love bug. She’s eager to belong. Per her trainer, Daisy may make a great therapy or helper dog. Because Daisy suffered some past issues, she’s intuitive to others who may be suffering or hurt. She wants to help make them feel better and will turn her full attention to that person in an effort to give them comfort. She gives and loves with her whole heart, but her heart and trust must be earned. Daisy will benefit from some gentle training. She’s learning to walk on a leash and some basic commands, which in turn builds her confidence. 

Daisy loves belly rubs, she loves chasing a ball and will give her paw to those she trusts. She loves playing with other dogs and when she does, you can see fully her wonderful personality. Dogs give her confidence and she is often seen playing with Faith, another dog that we rescued with her.    

Daisy is terrific young dog. She is going to be a wonderful companion to the person or family willing to go slow with her, gain her trust and help her forget her past. She longs to be a loyal companion. If you’re able to give Daisy a forever home filled with consistency, love and patience, you will be richly rewarded. She is a gem. 

If interested in Daisy, please submit an application online at: https://www.charlessmithgallhumanesociety.org/page/dog-adoption-application 
Once an application is submitted online, you will receive an email saying your application has been successfully submitted.  If you don’t receive this email within 24 hours, please check to make sure all application fields were completed or please call our shelter at 706-865-4135. All adopters must complete an approval process which involves a reference check with current/recent vet and a brief home visit if located in the immediate area. We do permit out of state adoptions. Adopters MUST come to the shelter to transport their new family member home. We do not ship nor do we transport them to their new homes. Adoption policies and application procedures are detailed at the shelter website: http://smithgallhumanesociety.org/ under tab All Adoptable Animals.
Charles Smithgall Humane Society (CSHS) is a No kill shelter. Animals in our care remain safe with us until adopted. Resident animals are primarily owner relinquished and also accepted from local Animal Control. The facility usually is operating at capacity with a list of animals waiting for space to open.
Adoptions and meet and greets are being scheduled by appointment only. Please call our office, email us or complete an application and someone will be in touch just as soon as they can. 
Location: 4823 Helen Hwy., Sautee, GA 30571, Phone: 706-865-4135
Email: smithgallhumanesociety@windstream.net
Our shelter in Sautee GA is located about 3 miles south of the alpine town of Helen in northeast GA.

animal.description:
Meet Topper
Topper is a stunning young dog at nine months. We think he’s a Catahoula/Terrier mix weighing 46 lbs. He was rescued from a high-kill shelter, along with Faith and Daisy. Topper is settling into the safety of our shelter where his personality comes out more every day. 
Topper is on the quiet side, chewing on a bone or his toys, until someone engages him to play or go for a walk. He LOVES attention and is very affectionate. He’s also a silly boy, loves to chase balls and will drag his blanket around with him. He’s learning some commands, but is often more interested in watching the goings on around him. He enjoys his walks and being outside. He has good energy and will do best with an active family or person. We haven’t yet tested Topper with other dogs or cats, but will do so for potential adopters. Topper will make for a wonderful companion. He longs to be someone’s special doggo and will be very loyal in return. 
He is quick to capture your heart and not let go. If you’re looking for an amazingly wonderful dog to welcome to your life, Topper may just be who you’re looking for. 
If interested in Topper, please submit an application online at: https://www.charlessmithgallhumanesociety.org/page/dog-adoption-application

animal.description:
Meet Cassiopeia! Cassie is a sweet girl who loves nothing more than to be around her people. She's always ready to go for a walk or play a rousing game of tug-of-war. When Cassiopeia isn't chewing on her toys or watching squirrels out the window, she loves snuggling up to watch a movie. Cassie is potty trained and crate trained. At night, she sleeps in her foster mom's room. Cassiopeia would do best in a home with no small dogs or cats. Cassie would also prefer an adult-only home or a family with teenage children. Cassie would love a family that is willing to give her the time and space to let her get comfortable so she can show off her amazing personality! Cassiopeia is incredibly smart and eager to please and has shown great affinity for learning new tricks. We can't wait to find Cassie a forever family who will give her the time, love, and patience to be the amazing dog that she is. Check out this video of her being a good girl! https://youtu.be/4sak8iiaGdg

We believe Cassiopeia is an American Staffordshire Terrier mix and was born around 6/1/2019. She weighs 40 lbs. She is is fostered in a private home in Lincoln. The adoption fee is $300 which covers vaccines, a microchip, and a spay/neuter(when old enough). The adoption fee helps cover the cost of these vetting procedures. Unless the bio is marked adoption pending, s/he is still available for adoption. If youre interested in adopting this puppy, please submit an inquiry or email BraveAnimalRescue@gmail.com to ask about our adoption process (please check your spam or junk email if you do not hear back from us within a few business days). We are 100% volunteer staffed and will respond to your email as soon as possible. After you have submitted an application and been approved, we will set up a meet and greet between you and the puppy. Preference is given to applicants with a verifiable vetting history, fenced yard, and homeownership. Please be sure to follow us on Facebook and Instagram to learn more about Brave Animal Rescue and our mission.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire and e-mail it to adoptioncenter@homewardtrails.org

Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. You can make an appointment to meet available dogs at our ADOPTION CENTER by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet and available cats at MEOW PALACE by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1. 

For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time. 

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE: http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Bolin, a MD native, is looking for his forever home! He is very social with people and other dogs but would do best in an adult only home. He can get over excited, jumpy and mouthy. He also needs a calmer type home environement where he will not be overwhelmed with too many people in his space. He would do best in a single family home/townhouse or condo that has direct access to the outside as opposed to apartment-style living. He has a strong prey drive and is not recommended to live with cats. He is part of the Go Fetch Program! 

Adoption Coordinator: Homeward Trails Adoption Center
Location: Adoption Center
The adoption fee for this dog is waived. This fee includes spay/neuter and microchip.

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program

animal.description:
Female/spayed
11 years
60lbs
Owner Surrender

Poor Delilah lived her life on a chain.  If you look in her eyes they seem sad and she bears the scars from a lifetime of neglect.  She must have had chronic ear infections to the point that her ear feels like leather, she has a dermal growth or cyst on the side of her face, her teeth are worn and she is stiff in her hips.  Delila arrived with her son Crane who is a nice guy but completely overwhelmed as he has probably never left that one back yard.  Despite her age and wear, Delilah as pep in her step.  She loves to go for walks and is happy to meet new people.  She is calm, appreciative of attention and loves a soft bed.  We hope that Delilah can find a home for the rest of her days to show her how wonderful people, soft beds and a loving touch can be. 

While Delilah loved being with her son Crane - she seems to be reactive to other dogs at this point. 

Please note:

At this time, our dog kennels are open for general visitation without a prior appointment. We will, however, be limiting the number of persons in the kennel area at one time, and we appreciate your patience.

Visits with cats and/or critters still require that an appointment be made in advance. To schedule your appointment, please call us at (703) 792-6465, or email us at animalshelter@pwcgov.org.

All persons will be required to wear a face mask when visiting the PWC Animal Shelter. This requirement complies with Governor Ralph Northam's Executive Order No.63 (https://bit.ly/2AnqGXd).

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please contact Kelly (kellymbetz1@gmail.com) for more information about this pet.Bailey has special needs. Please read the complete listing before applying.Bailey has problems with food. She needs to be on a special diet, and she requires multiple small meals per day. She presents with issues similar to megaesophegus, but her barium swallow test was clear. When she came into rescue, she was emaciated from being unable to keep down her food. Her homemade diet and very small meals every 2 hours during the day are working well. She is gaining weight and keeping her food down.She also had skin and ear infections when she came to rescue. Dietary changes and a Cytopoint shot have made a huge difference for her, but in typical Frenchie fashion, it will be a lifetime battle.Bailey spent her first 4 years in a situation where she was over bred and neglected. She is now spayed, so that will never be an issue again.Bailey's inner diva is coming out. She needs to be the only dog as she is reactive to other dogs over food, toys, and even affection from her people.When it comes to personality, Bailey is all Frenchie. She loves people. She's a smart girl, but she views many commands as suggestions from her minions rather than requirements. She loves to ride in the car, and she won't miss out on a good snuggle.Bailey's ideal home will have someone around to provide her with small meals throughout the day. An adopter with brachycephalic experience is also highly desirable.
Her adoption donation includes spaying, vaccinations, implanting of a microchip, application of flea meds and worming.
Bailey is in foster care so please complete an application at our website (www.castawaycritters.org) before meeting her. Completing an application does not obligate you to adopt; however, it is required. Applications are processed in the order received in an effort to find the best match possible for both the dog and the adopter.

Linus recently arrived at our shelter with his mother, Lucy (relinquished by their former family).  They appear to be Bluetick coonhound mixes.  Upon his arrival, Linus was extremely thin.  We have been loving him into his full being and keeping him well-fed.  As you can see, Linus is looking good with all of that special TLC.  The boy is full of energy and will need an active lifestyle with plenty of exercise.

animal.description:
Meet Jasper! Jasper is a Pure Breed approx., 80-90-pounds, AKC yellow Labrador born January 13, 2018. He will be 3 years old mid-January. Jasper comes to us to be rehomed due to his fathers heavy traveling schedule. Jasper is a good boy that will require a home with a stay-at-home or work-from-home family member that can give Jasper the attention and time he deserves since he does experience some separation anxiety. We also require he goes to a home that has a large fenced in yard, so when he is not inside, he has a place to go lay in the sun, play or potty.
Jasper is fine around other dogs, very obedient and understand basic cues (sit, shake, paw, laydown, come). He has taken obedience classes. He LOVES people and water! He is not used to children, but appears to be fine around them but older kids or teens would be ideal if going to a family home. Jasper would also do well in a home without children and just another dog his size he can hang out with and play.
Jasper lets you take toys away, isn’t afraid of storms and can be a bit stubborn; so, he will require continuous obedience training and equally important a Labbie leader that can keep well-balanced.
Jasper is full of energy so he will need a home that can give him plenty of attention; exercise routinely and another dog his size and energy level to pal around with. Jasper is housebroken and crate trained.
If you are interested in this boy you would be required to be the right fit and must complete our online pre-adoption application http://www.southernskiesrescue.org/adoption-application
